# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: game-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] In game theory, a **cooperative** or **coalitional game** is a game with groups of players who form binding "coalitions" with external enforcement of cooperative behavior (e.g. through contract law).
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] This is different from non-cooperative games in which there is either no possibility to forge alliances or all agreements need to be self-enforcing (e.g. through credible threats).
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Cooperative games are analysed by focusing on coalitions that can be formed, and the joint actions that groups can take and the resulting collective payoffs.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] A cooperative game is given by specifying a value for every coalition.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Formally, the coalitional game consists of a finite set of players N , called the *grand coalition*, and a *characteristic function* $v:2^{N}\to \mathbb {R}$ from the set of all possible coalitions of players to a set of payments that satisfies $v(\emptyset )=0$ .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The function describes how much collective payoff a set of players can gain by forming a coalition.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Cooperative game theory is a branch of game theory that deals with the study of games where players can form coalitions, cooperate with one another, and make binding agreements.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The theory offers mathematical methods for analysing scenarios in which two or more players are required to make choices that will affect other players wellbeing.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Let $S\subsetneq N$ be a non-empty coalition of players.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] In other words, we simply restrict our attention to coalitions contained in S .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Subgames are useful because they allow us to apply solution concepts defined for the grand coalition on smaller coalitions.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Characteristic functions are often assumed to be superadditive (Owen 1995, p.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] $v(S\cup T)\geq v(S)+v(T)$ whenever $S,T\subseteq N$ satisfy $S\cap T=\emptyset$ .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] $S\subseteq T\Rightarrow v(S)\leq v(T)$ .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] This follows from superadditivity. i.e. if payoffs are normalized so singleton coalitions have zero value.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] A coalitional game v is considered **simple** if payoffs are either 1 or 0, i.e. coalitions are either "winning" or "losing".
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Equivalently, a **simple game** can be defined as a collection W of coalitions, where the members of W are called **winning** coalitions, and the others **losing** coalitions.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] It is sometimes assumed that a simple game is nonempty or that it does not contain an empty set.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] However, in other areas of mathematics, simple games are also called hypergraphs or Boolean functions (logic functions).
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The restrictions that various axioms for simple games impose on their Nakamura number were also studied extensively.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] In particular, a computable simple game without a veto player has a Nakamura number greater than 3 only if it is a *proper* and *non-strong* game.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Let *G* be a strategic (non-cooperative) game.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Then, assuming that coalitions have the ability to enforce coordinated behaviour, there are several cooperative games associated with *G*.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] These games are often referred to as *representations of G*.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The main assumption in cooperative game theory is that the grand coalition N will form.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The challenge is then to allocate the payoff $v(N)$ among the players in some way.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Researchers have proposed different solution concepts based on different notions of fairness.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] An efficient payoff vector is called a *pre-imputation*, and an individually rational pre-imputation is called an imputation.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The stable set of a game (also known as the *von Neumann-Morgenstern solution* (von Neumann & Morgenstern 1944)) was the first solution proposed for games with more than 2 players.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Let v be a game and let x , y be two imputations of v .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Then x *dominates* y if some coalition $S\neq \emptyset$ satisfies $x_{i}>y_{i},\forall ~i\in S$ and $\sum _{i\in S}x_{i}\leq v(S)$ .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] In other words, players in S prefer the payoffs from x to those from y , and they can threaten to leave the grand coalition if y is used because the payoff they obtain on their own is at least as large as the allocation they receive under x .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Von Neumann and Morgenstern saw the stable set as the collection of acceptable behaviours in a society: None is clearly preferred to any other, but for each unacceptable behaviour there is a preferred alternative.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The definition is very general allowing the concept to be used in a wide variety of game formats.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] In words, the core is the set of imputations under which no coalition has a value greater than the sum of its members' payoffs.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Therefore, no coalition has incentive to leave the grand coalition and receive a larger payoff.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] For simple games, there is another notion of the core, when each player is assumed to have preferences on a set X of alternatives.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] A *profile* is a list $p=(\succ _{i}^{p})_{i\in N}$ of individual preferences $\succ _{i}^{p}$ on X .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Here $x\succ _{i}^{p}y$ means that individual i prefers alternative x to y at profile p .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Given a simple game v and a profile p , a *dominance* relation $\succ _{v}^{p}$ is defined on X by $x\succ _{v}^{p}y$ if and only if there is a winning coalition S (i.e., $v(S)=1$ ) satisfying $x\succ _{i}^{p}y$ for all $i\in S$ .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The *Nakamura number* of a simple game is the minimal number of winning coalitions with empty intersection.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] *Nakamura's theorem* states that the core $C(v,p)$ is nonempty for all profiles p of *acyclic* (alternatively, *transitive*) preferences if and only if X is finite *and* the cardinal number (the number of elements) of X is less than the Nakamura number of v .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] A variant by Kumabe and Mihara states that the core $C(v,p)$ is nonempty for all profiles p of preferences that have a *maximal element* if and only if the cardinal number of X is less than the Nakamura number of v .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Because the core may be empty, a generalization was introduced in (Shapley & Shubik 1966).
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Clearly, regardless of whether the core is empty, the strong $\varepsilon$ -core will be non-empty for a large enough value of $\varepsilon$ and empty for a small enough (possibly negative) value of $\varepsilon$ .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Following this line of reasoning, the *least-core*, introduced in (Maschler, Peleg & Shapley 1979), is the intersection of all non-empty strong $\varepsilon$ -cores.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] It can also be viewed as the strong $\varepsilon$ -core for the smallest value of $\varepsilon$ that makes the set non-empty (Bilbao 2000).
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The *Shapley value* is the unique payoff vector that is efficient, symmetric, and satisfies monotonicity.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] It was introduced by Lloyd Shapley (Shapley 1953) who showed that it is the unique payoff vector that is efficient, symmetric, additive, and assigns zero payoffs to dummy players.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The Shapley value of a superadditive game is individually rational, but this is not true in general.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Let $v:2^{N}\to \mathbb {R}$ be a game, and let $x\in \mathbb {R} ^{N}$ be an efficient payoff vector.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] the maximal amount player *i* can gain without the cooperation of player *j* by withdrawing from the grand coalition *N* under payoff vector *x*, assuming that the other players in *i'*s withdrawing coalition are satisfied with their payoffs under *x*.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The maximum surplus is a way to measure one player's bargaining power over another.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Intuitively, player *i* has more bargaining power than player *j* with respect to imputation *x* if $s_{ij}^{v}(x)>s_{ji}^{v}(x)$ , but player *j* is immune to player *i'*s threats if $x_{j}=v(j)$ , because he can obtain this payoff on his own.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The kernel contains all imputations where no player has this bargaining power over another.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] This solution concept was first introduced in (Davis & Maschler 1965).
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The *Harsanyi dividend* (named after John Harsanyi, who used it to generalize the Shapley value in 1963) identifies the surplus that is created by a coalition of players in a cooperative game.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] To specify this surplus, the worth of this coalition is corrected by subtracting the surplus that was already created by subcoalitions.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] An explicit formula for the dividend is given by ${\textstyle d_{v}(S)=\sum _{T\subseteq S}(-1)^{|S\setminus T|}v(T)}$ .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The function $d_{v}:2^{N}\to \mathbb {R}$ is also known as the Möbius inverse of $v:2^{N}\to \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Indeed, we can recover v from $d_{v}$ by help of the formula ${\textstyle v(S)=d_{v}(S)+\sum _{T\subsetneq S}d_{v}(T)}$ .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Let $v:2^{N}\to \mathbb {R}$ be a game, and let $x\in \mathbb {R} ^{N}$ be a payoff vector.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The *excess* of x for a coalition $S\subseteq N$ is the quantity $v(S)-\sum _{i\in S}x_{i}$ ; that is, the gain that players in coalition S can obtain if they withdraw from the grand coalition N under payoff x and instead take the payoff $v(S)$ .
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The *nucleolus* of v is the imputation for which the vector of excesses of all coalitions (a vector in $\mathbb {R} ^{2^{N}}$ ) is smallest in the leximin order.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The nucleolus was introduced in (Schmeidler 1969).
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] (Maschler, Peleg & Shapley 1979) gave a more intuitive description: Starting with the least-core, record the coalitions for which the right-hand side of the inequality in the definition of $C_{\varepsilon }(v)$ cannot be further reduced without making the set empty.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Continue decreasing the right-hand side for the remaining coalitions, until it cannot be reduced without making the set empty.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Record the new set of coalitions for which the inequalities hold at equality; continue decreasing the right-hand side of remaining coalitions and repeat this process as many times as necessary until all coalitions have been recorded.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The resulting payoff vector is the nucleolus.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Introduced by Shapley in (Shapley 1971), convex cooperative games capture the intuitive property some games have of "snowballing".
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] that is, "the incentives for joining a coalition increase as the coalition grows" (Shapley 1971), leading to the aforementioned snowball effect.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] For cost games, the inequalities are reversed, so that we say the cost game is *convex* if the characteristic function is submodular.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Submodular and supermodular set functions are also studied in combinatorial optimization.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Many of the results in (Shapley 1971) have analogues in (Edmonds 1970), where submodular functions were first presented as generalizations of matroids.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] In this context, the core of a convex cost game is called the *base polyhedron*, because its elements generalize base properties of matroids.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] However, the optimization community generally considers submodular functions to be the discrete analogues of convex functions (Lovász 1983), because the minimization of both types of functions is computationally tractable.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Unfortunately, this conflicts directly with Shapley's original definition of supermodular functions as "convex".
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Corporate strategic decisions can develop and create value through cooperative game theory.
[src:game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] This means that cooperative game theory can become the strategic theory of the firm, and different CGT solutions can simulate different institutions.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Introduced by John Maynard Smith and George R.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Price in 1972/3, it is an important concept in behavioural ecology, evolutionary psychology, mathematical game theory and economics, with applications in other fields such as anthropology, philosophy and political science.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Evolutionarily stable strategies were defined and introduced by John Maynard Smith and George R.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Such was the time taken in peer-reviewing the paper for *Nature* that this was preceded by a 1972 essay by Maynard Smith in a book of essays titled *On Evolution*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] The 1972 essay is sometimes cited instead of the 1973 paper, but university libraries are much more likely to have copies of *Nature*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Papers in *Nature* are usually short; in 1974, Maynard Smith published a longer paper in the *Journal of Theoretical Biology*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Maynard Smith explains further in his 1982 book *Evolution and the Theory of Games*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In fact, the ESS has become so central to game theory that often no citation is given, as the reader is assumed to be familiar with it.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Maynard Smith mathematically formalised a verbal argument made by Price, which he read while peer-reviewing Price's paper.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] When Maynard Smith realized that the somewhat disorganised Price was not ready to revise his article for publication, he offered to add Price as co-author.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] 174 of the Postscript in his, 1982 work *Evolution and the Theory of Games* argues that the concept of an ESS is itself polyphyletic (i.e. derives from more than one common evolutionary ancestral group or ancestor).
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In this he not only mentions Price but also list various other sources for the concept.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] But the concept proper was derived from R.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Hamilton's work on sex ratios, derived from Fisher's principle, especially Hamilton's (1967) concept of an unbeatable strategy.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Maynard Smith was jointly awarded the 1999 Crafoord Prize for his development of the concept of evolutionarily stable strategies and the application of game theory to the evolution of behaviour.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] The Nash equilibrium is the traditional solution concept in game theory.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] It depends on the cognitive abilities of the players.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] It is assumed that players are aware of the structure of the game and consciously try to predict the moves of their opponents and to maximize their own payoffs.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In addition, it is presumed that all the players know this (see common knowledge).
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] These assumptions are then used to explain why players choose Nash equilibrium strategies.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Evolutionarily stable strategies are motivated entirely differently.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Here, it is presumed that the players' strategies are biologically encoded and heritable.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Individuals have no control over their strategy and need not be aware of the game.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] They reproduce and are subject to the forces of natural selection, with the payoffs of the game representing reproductive success (biological fitness).
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] It is imagined that alternative strategies of the game occasionally occur, via a process like mutation.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] To be an ESS, a strategy must be resistant to these alternatives.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Given the radically different motivating assumptions, it may come as a surprise that ESSes and Nash equilibria often coincide.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In fact, every ESS corresponds to a Nash equilibrium, but some Nash equilibria are not ESSes.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] An ESS is a refined or modified form of a Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] (See the next section for examples which contrast the two.) In a Nash equilibrium, if all players adopt their respective parts, no player can *benefit* by switching to any alternative strategy.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In a two player game, it is a strategy pair.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Let E(*S*,*T*) represent the payoff for playing strategy *S* against strategy *T*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In this definition, a strategy *T*≠*S* can be a neutral alternative to *S* (scoring equally well, but not better).
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] A Nash equilibrium is presumed to be stable even if *T* scores equally, on the assumption that there is no long-term incentive for players to adopt *T* instead of *S*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] This fact represents the point of departure of the ESS.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Maynard Smith and Price specify two conditions for a strategy *S* to be an ESS.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] The first condition is sometimes called a *strict* Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] The second is sometimes called "Maynard Smith's second condition".
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] The second condition means that although strategy *T* is neutral with respect to the payoff against strategy *S*, the population of players who continue to play strategy *S* has an advantage when playing against *T*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] There is also an alternative, stronger definition of ESS, due to Thomas.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] This places a different emphasis on the role of the Nash equilibrium concept in the ESS concept.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In this formulation, the first condition specifies that the strategy is a Nash equilibrium, and the second specifies that Maynard Smith's second condition is met.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Note that the two definitions are not precisely equivalent: for example, each pure strategy in the coordination game below is an ESS by the first definition but not the second.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] This formulation more clearly highlights the role of the Nash equilibrium condition in the ESS.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] It also allows for a natural definition of related concepts such as a weak ESS or an evolutionarily stable set.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In most simple games, the ESSes and Nash equilibria coincide perfectly.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] For instance, in the prisoner's dilemma there is only one Nash equilibrium, and its strategy (*Defect*) is also an ESS.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Some games may have Nash equilibria that are not ESSes.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] For example, in harm thy neighbor (whose payoff matrix is shown here) both (*A*, *A*) and (*B*, *B*) are Nash equilibria, since players cannot do better by switching away from either.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] However, only *B* is an ESS (and a strong Nash).
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] *A* is not an ESS, so *B* can neutrally invade a population of *A* strategists and predominate, because *B* scores higher against *B* than *A* does against *B*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] This dynamic is captured by Maynard Smith's second condition, since E(*A*, *A*) = E(*B*, *A*), but it is not the case that E(*A*,*B*) > E(*B*,*B*).
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Nash equilibria with equally scoring alternatives can be ESSes.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] For example, in the game *Harm everyone*, *C* is an ESS because it satisfies Maynard Smith's second condition.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] *D* strategists may temporarily invade a population of *C* strategists by scoring equally well against *C*, but they pay a price when they begin to play against each other; *C* scores better against *D* than does *D*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Even if a game has pure strategy Nash equilibria, it might be that none of those pure strategies are ESS.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] There are two pure strategy Nash equilibria in this game (*Swerve*, *Stay*) and (*Stay*, *Swerve*).
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] However, in the absence of an uncorrelated asymmetry, neither *Swerve* nor *Stay* are ESSes.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] There is a third Nash equilibrium, a mixed strategy which is an ESS for this game (see Hawk-dove game and Best response for explanation).
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] This last example points to an important difference between Nash equilibria and ESS.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Nash equilibria are defined on *strategy sets* (a specification of a strategy for each player), while ESS are defined in terms of strategies themselves.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] The equilibria defined by ESS must always be symmetric, and thus have fewer equilibrium points.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In population biology, the two concepts of an *evolutionarily stable strategy* (ESS) and an *evolutionarily stable state* are closely linked but describe different situations.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In an evolutionarily stable *strategy,* if all the members of a population adopt it, no mutant strategy can invade.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Once virtually all members of the population use this strategy, there is no 'rational' alternative.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In an evolutionarily stable *state,* a population's genetic composition is restored by selection after a disturbance, if the disturbance is not too large.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] An evolutionarily stable state is a dynamic property of a population that returns to using a strategy, or mix of strategies, if it is perturbed from that initial state.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] It is part of population genetics, dynamical system, or evolutionary game theory.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] This is now called convergent stability.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Thomas (1984) applies the term ESS to an individual strategy which may be mixed, and evolutionarily stable population state to a population mixture of pure strategies which may be formally equivalent to the mixed ESS.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Whether a population is evolutionarily stable does not relate to its genetic diversity: it can be genetically monomorphic or polymorphic.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In the classic definition of an ESS, no mutant strategy can invade.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In finite populations, any mutant could in principle invade, albeit at low probability, implying that no ESS can exist.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In an infinite population, an ESS can instead be defined as a strategy which, should it become invaded by a new mutant strategy with probability p, would be able to counterinvade from a single starting individual with probability >p, as illustrated by the evolution of bet-hedging.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] A common model of altruism and social cooperation is the Prisoner's dilemma.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Here a group of players would collectively be better off if they could play *Cooperate*, but since *Defect* fares better each individual player has an incentive to play *Defect*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] One solution to this problem is to introduce the possibility of retaliation by having individuals play the game repeatedly against the same player.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In the so-called *iterated* Prisoner's dilemma, the same two individuals play the prisoner's dilemma over and over.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] While the Prisoner's dilemma has only two strategies (*Cooperate* and *Defect*), the iterated Prisoner's dilemma has a huge number of possible strategies.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Since an individual can have different contingency plan for each history and the game may be repeated an indefinite number of times, there may in fact be an infinite number of such contingency plans.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Three simple contingency plans which have received substantial attention are *Always Defect*, *Always Cooperate*, and *Tit for Tat*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] The first two strategies do the same thing regardless of the other player's actions, while the latter responds on the next round by doing what was done to it on the previous round—it responds to *Cooperate* with *Cooperate* and *Defect* with *Defect*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] If the entire population plays *Tit-for-Tat* and a mutant arises who plays *Always Defect*, *Tit-for-Tat* will outperform *Always Defect*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] If the population of the mutant becomes too large — the percentage of the mutant will be kept small.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] *Tit for Tat* is therefore an ESS, *with respect to **only** these two strategies*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] On the other hand, an island of *Always Defect* players will be stable against the invasion of a few *Tit-for-Tat* players, but not against a large number of them.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] If we introduce *Always Cooperate*, a population of *Tit-for-Tat* is no longer an ESS.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Since a population of *Tit-for-Tat* players always cooperates, the strategy *Always Cooperate* behaves identically in this population.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] As a result, a mutant who plays *Always Cooperate* will not be eliminated.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] However, even though a population of *Always Cooperate* and *Tit-for-Tat* can coexist, if there is a small percentage of the population that is *Always Defect*, the selective pressure is against *Always Cooperate*, and in favour of *Tit-for-Tat*.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] This is due to the lower payoffs of cooperating than those of defecting in case the opponent defects.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] This demonstrates the difficulties in applying the formal definition of an ESS to games with large strategy spaces, and has motivated some to consider alternatives.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] The fields of sociobiology and evolutionary psychology attempt to explain animal and human behavior and social structures, largely in terms of evolutionarily stable strategies.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Sociopathy (chronic antisocial or criminal behavior) may be a result of a combination of two such strategies.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] Evolutionarily stable strategies were originally considered for biological evolution, but they can apply to other contexts.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] In fact, there are stable states for a large class of adaptive dynamics.
[src:game-theory/evolutionarily-stable-strategy] As a result, they can be used to explain human behaviours that lack any genetic influences.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Modern game theory began with the idea of mixed-strategy equilibria in two-person zero-sum games and its proof by John von Neumann.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Von Neumann's original proof used the Brouwer fixed-point theorem on continuous mappings into compact convex sets, which became a standard method in game theory and mathematical economics.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] His paper was followed by *Theory of Games and Economic Behavior* (1944), co-written with Oskar Morgenstern, which considered cooperative games of several players.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The second edition provided an axiomatic theory of expected utility, which allowed mathematical statisticians and economists to treat decision-making under uncertainty.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Game theory was developed extensively in the 1950s, and was explicitly applied to evolution in the 1970s, although similar developments go back at least as far as the 1930s.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Game theory has been widely recognized as an important tool in many fields.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] John Maynard Smith was awarded the Crafoord Prize for his application of evolutionary game theory in 1999, and fifteen game theorists have won the Nobel Prize in economics as of 2020, including most recently Paul Milgrom and Robert B.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Discussions on the mathematics of games began long before the rise of modern, mathematical game theory.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Cardano wrote on games of chance in *Liber de ludo aleae* (*Book on Games of Chance*), written around 1564 but published posthumously in 1663.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Influenced by the work of Fermat and Pascal on the problem of points, Huygens developed the concept of expectation on reasoning about the structure of games of chance, publishing his gambling calculus in *De ratiociniis in ludo aleæ* (*On Reasoning in Games of Chance*) in 1657.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In 1713, a letter attributed to Charles Waldegrave, an active Jacobite and uncle to British diplomat James Waldegrave, analyzed a game called "le her".
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Waldegrave provided a minimax mixed strategy solution to a two-person version of the card game, and the problem is now known as the Waldegrave problem.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In 1838, Antoine Augustin Cournot provided a model of competition in oligopolies.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Though he did not refer to it as such, he presented a solution that is the Nash equilibrium of the game in his *Recherches sur les principes mathématiques de la théorie des richesses* (*Researches into the Mathematical Principles of the Theory of Wealth*).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In 1883, Joseph Bertrand critiqued Cournot's model as unrealistic, providing an alternative model of price competition which would later be formalized by Francis Ysidro Edgeworth.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In 1913, Ernst Zermelo published *Über eine Anwendung der Mengenlehre auf die Theorie des Schachspiels* (*On an Application of Set Theory to the Theory of the Game of Chess*), which proved that the optimal chess strategy is strictly determined.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The work of John von Neumann established game theory as its own independent field in the early-to-mid 20th century, with von Neumann publishing his paper *On the Theory of Games of Strategy* in 1928.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Von Neumann's original proof used Brouwer's fixed-point theorem on continuous mappings into compact convex sets, which became a standard method in game theory and mathematical economics.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Von Neumann's work in game theory culminated in his 1944 book *Theory of Games and Economic Behavior*, co-authored with Oskar Morgenstern.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The second edition of this book provided an axiomatic theory of utility, which reincarnated Daniel Bernoulli's old theory of utility (of money) as an independent discipline.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] This foundational work contains the method for finding mutually consistent solutions for two-person zero-sum games.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Subsequent work focused primarily on cooperative game theory, which analyzes optimal strategies for groups of individuals, presuming that they can enforce agreements between them about proper strategies.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In his 1938 book *Applications aux Jeux de Hasard* and earlier notes, Émile Borel proved a minimax theorem for two-person zero-sum matrix games only when the pay-off matrix is symmetric and provided a solution to a non-trivial infinite game (known in English as Blotto game).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Borel conjectured the non-existence of mixed-strategy equilibria in finite two-person zero-sum games, a conjecture that was proved false by von Neumann.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In 1950, John Nash developed a criterion for mutual consistency of players' strategies known as the Nash equilibrium, applicable to a wider variety of games than the criterion proposed by von Neumann and Morgenstern.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Nash proved that every finite n-player, non-zero-sum (not just two-player zero-sum) non-cooperative game has what is now known as a Nash equilibrium in mixed strategies.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Game theory experienced a flurry of activity in the 1950s, during which the concepts of the core, the extensive form game, fictitious play, repeated games, and the Shapley value were developed.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The 1950s also saw the first applications of game theory to philosophy and political science.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The first mathematical discussion of the prisoner's dilemma appeared, and an experiment was undertaken by mathematicians Merrill M.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Flood and Melvin Dresher, as part of the RAND Corporation's investigations into game theory.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] RAND pursued the studies because of possible applications to global nuclear strategy.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In 1965, Reinhard Selten introduced his solution concept of subgame perfect equilibria, which further refined the Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Later he would introduce trembling hand perfection as well.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In 1994 Nash, Selten and Harsanyi became Economics Nobel Laureates for their contributions to economic game theory.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In the 1970s, game theory was extensively applied in biology, largely as a result of the work of John Maynard Smith and his evolutionarily stable strategy.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In addition, the concepts of correlated equilibrium, trembling hand perfection and common knowledge were introduced and analyzed.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In 1994, John Nash was awarded the Nobel Memorial Prize in the Economic Sciences for his contribution to game theory.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Nash's most famous contribution to game theory is the concept of the Nash equilibrium, which is a solution concept for non-cooperative games, published in 1951.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] A Nash equilibrium is a set of strategies, one for each player, such that no player can improve their payoff by unilaterally changing their strategy.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In 2005, game theorists Thomas Schelling and Robert Aumann followed Nash, Selten, and Harsanyi as Nobel Laureates.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Schelling worked on dynamic models, early examples of evolutionary game theory.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Aumann contributed more to the equilibrium school, introducing equilibrium coarsening and correlated equilibria, and developing an extensive formal analysis of the assumption of common knowledge and of its consequences.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In 2007, Leonid Hurwicz, Eric Maskin, and Roger Myerson were awarded the Nobel Prize in Economics "for having laid the foundations of mechanism design theory".
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Myerson's contributions include the notion of proper equilibrium, and an important graduate text: *Game Theory, Analysis of Conflict*.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Hurwicz introduced and formalized the concept of incentive compatibility.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Shapley were awarded the Nobel Prize in Economics "for the theory of stable allocations and the practice of market design".
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In 2014, the Nobel went to game theorist Jean Tirole.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] A game is *cooperative* if the players are able to form binding commitments externally enforced (e.g. through contract law).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] A game is *non-cooperative* if players cannot form alliances or if all agreements need to be self-enforcing (e.g. through credible threats).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Cooperative games are often analyzed through the framework of *cooperative game theory*, which focuses on predicting which coalitions will form, the joint actions that groups take, and the resulting collective payoffs.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] It is different from *non-cooperative game theory* which focuses on predicting individual players' actions and payoffs by analyzing Nash equilibria.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Cooperative game theory provides a high-level approach as it describes only the structure and payoffs of coalitions, whereas non-cooperative game theory also looks at how strategic interaction will affect the distribution of payoffs.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] A symmetric game is a game where each player earns the same payoff when making the same choice.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In other words, the identity of the player does not change the resulting game facing the other player.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Many of the commonly studied 2×2 games are symmetric.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The standard representations of chicken, the prisoner's dilemma, and the stag hunt are all symmetric games.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The most commonly studied asymmetric games are games where there are not identical strategy sets for both players.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] For instance, the ultimatum game and similarly the dictator game have different strategies for each player.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] It is possible, however, for a game to have identical strategies for both players, yet be asymmetric.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] For example, the game pictured in this section's graphic is asymmetric despite having identical strategy sets for both players.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Zero-sum games (more generally, constant-sum games) are games in which choices by players can neither increase nor decrease the available resources.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In zero-sum games, the total benefit goes to all players in a game, for every combination of strategies, and always adds to zero (more informally, a player benefits only at the equal expense of others).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Poker exemplifies a zero-sum game (ignoring the possibility of the house's cut), because one wins exactly the amount one's opponents lose.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Other zero-sum games include matching pennies and most classical board games including Go and chess.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Many games studied by game theorists (including the famed prisoner's dilemma) are non-zero-sum games, because the outcome has net results greater or less than zero.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Informally, in non-zero-sum games, a gain by one player does not necessarily correspond with a loss by another.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Furthermore, *constant-sum games* correspond to activities like theft and gambling, but not to the fundamental economic situation in which there are potential gains from trade.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] It is possible to transform any constant-sum game into a (possibly asymmetric) zero-sum game by adding a dummy player (often called "the board") whose losses compensate the players' net winnings.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Simultaneous games are games where both players move simultaneously, or instead the later players are unaware of the earlier players' actions (making them *effectively* simultaneous).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Sequential games (a type of dynamic games) are games where players do not make decisions simultaneously, and player's earlier actions affect the outcome and decisions of other players.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] This need not be perfect information about every action of earlier players; it might be very little knowledge.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] For instance, a player may know that an earlier player did not perform one particular action, while they do not know which of the other available actions the first player actually performed.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The difference between simultaneous and sequential games is captured in the different representations discussed above.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Often, normal form is used to represent simultaneous games, while extensive form is used to represent sequential ones.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The transformation of extensive to normal form is one way, meaning that multiple extensive form games correspond to the same normal form.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Consequently, notions of equilibrium for simultaneous games are insufficient for reasoning about sequential games; see subgame perfection.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] An important subset of sequential games consists of games of perfect information.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] A game with perfect information means that all players, at every move in the game, know the previous history of the game and the moves previously made by all other players.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] An imperfect information game is played when the players do not know all moves already made by the opponent such as a simultaneous move game.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Examples of perfect-information games include tic-tac-toe, checkers, chess, and Go.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Many card games are games of imperfect information, such as poker and bridge.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Perfect information is often confused with complete information, which is a similar concept pertaining to the common knowledge of each player's sequence, strategies, and payoffs throughout gameplay.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Complete information requires that every player know the strategies and payoffs available to the other players but not necessarily the actions taken, whereas perfect information is knowledge of all aspects of the game and players.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Games of incomplete information can be reduced, however, to games of imperfect information by introducing "moves by nature".
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] One of the assumptions of the Nash equilibrium is that every player has correct beliefs about the actions of the other players.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] However, there are many situations in game theory where participants do not fully understand the characteristics of their opponents.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Negotiators may be unaware of their opponent's valuation of the object of negotiation, companies may be unaware of their opponent's cost functions, combatants may be unaware of their opponent's strengths, and jurors may be unaware of their colleague's interpretation of the evidence at trial.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In some cases, participants may know the character of their opponent well, but may not know how well their opponent knows his or her own character.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Bayesian game means a strategic game with incomplete information.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] For a strategic game, decision makers are players, and every player has a group of actions.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] A core part of the imperfect information specification is the set of states.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Every state completely describes a collection of characteristics relevant to the player such as their preferences and details about them.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] There must be a state for every set of features that some player believes may exist.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] For example, where Player 1 is unsure whether Player 2 would rather date her or get away from her, while Player 2 understands Player 1's preferences as before.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Due to the probability involved, the analysis of this situation requires to understand the player's preference for the draw, even though people are only interested in pure strategic equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Games in which the difficulty of finding an optimal strategy stems from the multiplicity of possible moves are called combinatorial games.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Games that involve imperfect information may also have a strong combinatorial character, for instance backgammon.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] There is no unified theory addressing combinatorial elements in games.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] There are, however, mathematical tools that can solve some particular problems and answer some general questions.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] These methods address games with higher combinatorial complexity than those usually considered in traditional (or "economic") game theory.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] A typical game that has been solved this way is Hex.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] A related field of study, drawing from computational complexity theory, is game complexity, which is concerned with estimating the computational difficulty of finding optimal strategies.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Research in artificial intelligence has addressed both perfect and imperfect information games that have very complex combinatorial structures (like chess, go, or backgammon) for which no provable optimal strategies have been found.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The practical solutions involve computational heuristics, like alpha–beta pruning or use of artificial neural networks trained by reinforcement learning, which make games more tractable in computing practice.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Much of game theory is concerned with finite, discrete games that have a finite number of players, moves, events, outcomes, etc.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Continuous games allow players to choose a strategy from a continuous strategy set.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] For instance, Cournot competition is typically modeled with players' strategies being any non-negative quantities, including fractional quantities.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Differential games such as the continuous pursuit and evasion game are continuous games where the evolution of the players' state variables is governed by differential equations.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The problem of finding an optimal strategy in a differential game is closely related to the optimal control theory.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In particular, there are two types of strategies: the open-loop strategies are found using the Pontryagin maximum principle while the closed-loop strategies are found using Bellman's Dynamic Programming method.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] A particular case of differential games are the games with a random time horizon.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In such games, the terminal time is a random variable with a given probability distribution function.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Therefore, the players maximize the mathematical expectation of the cost function.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] It was shown that the modified optimization problem can be reformulated as a discounted differential game over an infinite time interval.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Evolutionary game theory studies players who adjust their strategies over time according to rules that are not necessarily rational or farsighted.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In general, the evolution of strategies over time according to such rules is modeled as a Markov chain with a state variable such as the current strategy profile or how the game has been played in the recent past.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Such rules may feature imitation, optimization, or survival of the fittest.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In biology, such models can represent evolution, in which offspring adopt their parents' strategies and parents who play more successful strategies (i.e. corresponding to higher payoffs) have a greater number of offspring.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In the social sciences, such models typically represent strategic adjustment by players who play a game many times within their lifetime and, consciously or unconsciously, occasionally adjust their strategies.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Individual decision problems with stochastic outcomes are sometimes considered "one-player games".
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] They may be modeled using similar tools within the related disciplines of decision theory, operations research, and areas of artificial intelligence, particularly AI planning (with uncertainty) and multi-agent system.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Although these fields may have different motivators, the mathematics involved are substantially the same, e.g. using Markov decision processes (MDP).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Stochastic outcomes can also be modeled in terms of game theory by adding a randomly acting player who makes "chance moves" ("moves by nature").
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] This player is not typically considered a third player in what is otherwise a two-player game, but merely serves to provide a roll of the dice where required by the game.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] For some problems, different approaches to modeling stochastic outcomes may lead to different solutions.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] For example, the difference in approach between MDPs and the minimax solution is that the latter considers the worst-case over a set of adversarial moves, rather than reasoning in expectation about these moves given a fixed probability distribution.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The minimax approach may be advantageous where stochastic models of uncertainty are not available, but may also be overestimating extremely unlikely (but costly) events, dramatically swaying the strategy in such scenarios if it is assumed that an adversary can force such an event to happen.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] General models that include all elements of stochastic outcomes, adversaries, and partial or noisy observability (of moves by other players) have also been studied.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The "gold standard" is considered to be partially observable stochastic game (POSG), but few realistic problems are computationally feasible in POSG representation.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] These are games the play of which is the development of the rules for another game, the target or subject game.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Metagames seek to maximize the utility value of the rule set developed.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The theory of metagames is related to mechanism design theory.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The term metagame analysis is also used to refer to a practical approach developed by Nigel Howard, whereby a situation is framed as a strategic game in which stakeholders try to realize their objectives by means of the options available to them.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Subsequent developments have led to the formulation of confrontation analysis.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Mean field game theory is the study of strategic decision making in very large populations of small interacting agents.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] This class of problems was considered in the economics literature by Boyan Jovanovic and Robert W.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Rosenthal, in the engineering literature by Peter E.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Caines, and by mathematicians Pierre-Louis Lions and Jean-Michel Lasry.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The games studied in game theory are well-defined mathematical objects.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] To be fully defined, a game must specify the following elements: the *players* of the game, the *information* and *actions* available to each player at each decision point, and the *payoffs* for each outcome.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] These equilibrium strategies determine an equilibrium to the game—a stable state in which either one outcome occurs or a set of outcomes occur with known probability.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Most cooperative games are presented in the characteristic function form, while the extensive and the normal forms are used to define noncooperative games.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The extensive form can be used to formalize games with a time sequencing of moves.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Extensive form games can be visualized using game trees (as pictured here).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Here each vertex (or node) represents a point of choice for a player.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The player is specified by a number listed by the vertex.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The lines out of the vertex represent a possible action for that player.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The payoffs are specified at the bottom of the tree.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The extensive form can be viewed as a multi-player generalization of a decision tree.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] To solve any extensive form game, backward induction must be used.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] It involves working backward up the game tree to determine what a rational player would do at the last vertex of the tree, what the player with the previous move would do given that the player with the last move is rational, and so on until the first vertex of the tree is reached.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The game pictured consists of two players.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The way this particular game is structured (i.e., with sequential decision making and perfect information), *Player 1* "moves" first by choosing either *F* or *U* (fair or unfair).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Next in the sequence, *Player 2*, who has now observed *Player 1*'s move, can choose to play either *A* or *R* (accept or reject).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Once *Player 2* has made their choice, the game is considered finished and each player gets their respective payoff, represented in the image as two numbers, where the first number represents Player 1's payoff, and the second number represents Player 2's payoff.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The extensive form can also capture simultaneous-move games and games with imperfect information.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] To represent it, either a dotted line connects different vertices to represent them as being part of the same information set (i.e. the players do not know at which point they are), or a closed line is drawn around them.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The normal (or strategic form) game is usually represented by a matrix which shows the players, strategies, and payoffs (see the example to the right).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] More generally it can be represented by any function that associates a payoff for each player with every possible combination of actions.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In the accompanying example there are two players; one chooses the row and the other chooses the column.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Each player has two strategies, which are specified by the number of rows and the number of columns.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The payoffs are provided in the interior.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The first number is the payoff received by the row player (Player 1 in our example); the second is the payoff for the column player (Player 2 in our example).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Suppose that Player 1 plays *Up* and that Player 2 plays *Left*.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Then Player 1 gets a payoff of 4, and Player 2 gets 3.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] When a game is presented in normal form, it is presumed that each player acts simultaneously or, at least, without knowing the actions of the other.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] If players have some information about the choices of other players, the game is usually presented in extensive form.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Every extensive-form game has an equivalent normal-form game, however, the transformation to normal form may result in an exponential blowup in the size of the representation, making it computationally impractical.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In cooperative game theory the characteristic function lists the payoff of each coalition.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] The origin of this formulation is in John von Neumann and Oskar Morgenstern's book.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Formally, a characteristic function is a function $v:2^{N}\to \mathbb {R}$ from the set of all possible coalitions of players to a set of payments, and also satisfies $v(\emptyset )=0$ .
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] Alternative game representation forms are used for some subclasses of games or adjusted to the needs of interdisciplinary research.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p01] In addition to classical game representations, some of the alternative representations also encode time related aspects.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] As a method of applied mathematics, game theory has been used to study a wide variety of human and animal behaviors.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] It was initially developed in economics to understand a large collection of economic behaviors, including behaviors of firms, markets, and consumers.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The first use of game-theoretic analysis was by Antoine Augustin Cournot in 1838 with his solution of the Cournot duopoly.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The use of game theory in the social sciences has expanded, and game theory has been applied to political, sociological, and psychological behaviors as well.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Although pre-twentieth-century naturalists such as Charles Darwin made game-theoretic kinds of statements, the use of game-theoretic analysis in biology began with Ronald Fisher's studies of animal behavior during the 1930s.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] This work predates the name "game theory", but it shares many important features with this field.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The developments in economics were later applied to biology largely by John Maynard Smith in his 1982 book *Evolution and the Theory of Games*.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In addition to being used to describe, predict, and explain behavior, game theory has also been used to develop theories of ethical or normative behavior and to prescribe such behavior.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In economics and philosophy, scholars have applied game theory to help in the understanding of good or proper behavior.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game-theoretic approaches have also been suggested in the philosophy of language and philosophy of science.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game-theoretic arguments of this type can be found as far back as Plato.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] An alternative version of game theory, called chemical game theory, represents the player's choices as metaphorical chemical reactant molecules called "knowlecules".
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Chemical game theory then calculates the outcomes as equilibrium solutions to a system of chemical reactions.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The primary use of game theory is to describe and model how human populations behave.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Some scholars believe that by finding the equilibria of games they can predict how actual human populations will behave when confronted with situations analogous to the game being studied.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] This particular view of game theory has been criticized .
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] It is argued that the assumptions made by game theorists are often violated when applied to real-world situations.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game theorists usually assume players act rationally, but in practice, human rationality and/or behavior often deviates from the model of rationality as used in game theory.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game theorists respond by comparing their assumptions to those used in physics.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Thus while their assumptions do not always hold, they can treat game theory as a reasonable scientific ideal akin to the models used by physicists.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] However, empirical work has shown that in some classic games, such as the centipede game, guess 2/3 of the average game, and the dictator game, people regularly do not play Nash equilibria.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] There is an ongoing debate regarding the importance of these experiments and whether the analysis of the experiments fully captures all aspects of the relevant situation.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Some game theorists, following the work of John Maynard Smith and George R.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Price, have turned to evolutionary game theory in order to resolve these issues.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] These models presume either no rationality or bounded rationality on the part of players.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Despite the name, evolutionary game theory does not necessarily presume natural selection in the biological sense.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Evolutionary game theory includes both biological as well as cultural evolution and also models of individual learning (for example, fictitious play dynamics).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Some scholars see game theory not as a predictive tool for the behavior of human beings, but as a suggestion for how people ought to behave.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Since a strategy, corresponding to a Nash equilibrium of a game constitutes one's best response to the actions of the other players – provided they are in (the same) Nash equilibrium – playing a strategy that is part of a Nash equilibrium seems appropriate.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] This normative use of game theory has also come under criticism.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game theory is a major method used in mathematical economics and business for modeling competing behaviors of interacting agents.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] This research usually focuses on particular sets of strategies known as "solution concepts" or "equilibria".
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] A common assumption is that players act rationally.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In non-cooperative games, the most famous of these is the Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] A set of strategies is a Nash equilibrium if each represents a best response to the other strategies.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] If all the players are playing the strategies in a Nash equilibrium, they have no unilateral incentive to deviate, since their strategy is the best they can do given what others are doing.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The payoffs of the game are generally taken to represent the utility of individual players.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] A prototypical paper on game theory in economics begins by presenting a game that is an abstraction of a particular economic situation.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] One or more solution concepts are chosen, and the author demonstrates which strategy sets in the presented game are equilibria of the appropriate type.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Economists and business professors suggest two primary uses (noted above): *descriptive* and *prescriptive*.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game theory also has an extensive use in a specific branch or stream of economics – Managerial Economics.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] One important usage of it in the field of managerial economics is in analyzing strategic interactions between firms.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] For example, firms may be competing in a market with limited resources, and game theory can help managers understand how their decisions impact their competitors and the overall market outcomes.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game theory can also be used to analyze cooperation between firms, such as in forming strategic alliances or joint ventures.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Another use of game theory in managerial economics is in analyzing pricing strategies.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] For example, firms may use game theory to determine the optimal pricing strategy based on how they expect their competitors to respond to their pricing decisions.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Overall, game theory serves as a useful tool for analyzing strategic interactions and decision making in the context of managerial economics.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The Chartered Institute of Procurement & Supply (CIPS) promotes knowledge and use of game theory within the context of business procurement.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] CIPS and TWS Partners have conducted a series of surveys designed to explore the understanding, awareness and application of game theory among procurement professionals.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Sensible decision-making is critical for the success of projects.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In project management, game theory is used to model the decision-making process of players, such as investors, project managers, contractors, sub-contractors, governments and customers.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Quite often, these players have competing interests, and sometimes their interests are directly detrimental to other players, making project management scenarios well-suited to be modeled by game theory.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Piraveenan (2019) in his review provides several examples where game theory is used to model project management scenarios.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] For instance, an investor typically has several investment options, and each option will likely result in a different project, and thus one of the investment options has to be chosen before the project charter can be produced.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Similarly, any large project involving subcontractors, for instance, a construction project, has a complex interplay between the main contractor (the project manager) and subcontractors, or among the subcontractors themselves, which typically has several decision points.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] For example, if there is an ambiguity in the contract between the contractor and subcontractor, each must decide how hard to push their case without jeopardizing the whole project, and thus their own stake in it.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Similarly, when projects from competing organizations are launched, the marketing personnel have to decide what is the best timing and strategy to market the project, or its resultant product or service, so that it can gain maximum traction in the face of competition.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In each of these scenarios, the required decisions depend on the decisions of other players who, in some way, have competing interests to the interests of the decision-maker, and thus can ideally be modeled using game theory.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Piraveenan summarizes that two-player games are predominantly used to model project management scenarios, and based on the identity of these players, five distinct types of games are used in project management.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In terms of types of games, both cooperative as well as non-cooperative, normal-form as well as extensive-form, and zero-sum as well as non-zero-sum are used to model various project management scenarios.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The application of game theory to political science is focused in the overlapping areas of fair division, political economy, public choice, war bargaining, positive political theory, and social choice theory.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In each of these areas, researchers have developed game-theoretic models in which the players are often voters, states, special interest groups, and politicians.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Early examples of game theory applied to political science are provided by Anthony Downs.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In his 1957 book *An Economic Theory of Democracy*, he applies the Hotelling firm location model to the political process.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In the Downsian model, political candidates commit to ideologies on a one-dimensional policy space.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Downs first shows how the political candidates will converge to the ideology preferred by the median voter if voters are fully informed, but then argues that voters choose to remain rationally ignorant which allows for candidate divergence.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game theory was applied in 1962 to the Cuban Missile Crisis during the presidency of John F.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] It has also been proposed that game theory explains the stability of any form of political government.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Taking the simplest case of a monarchy, for example, the king, being only one person, does not and cannot maintain his authority by personally exercising physical control over all or even any significant number of his subjects.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Sovereign control is instead explained by the recognition by each citizen that all other citizens expect each other to view the king (or other established government) as the person whose orders will be followed.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Coordinating communication among citizens to replace the sovereign is effectively barred, since conspiracy to replace the sovereign is generally punishable as a crime.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Thus, in a process that can be modeled by variants of the prisoner's dilemma, during periods of stability no citizen will find it rational to move to replace the sovereign, even if all the citizens know they would be better off if they were all to act collectively.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] A game-theoretic explanation for democratic peace is that public and open debate in democracies sends clear and reliable information regarding their intentions to other states.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In contrast, it is difficult to know the intentions of nondemocratic leaders, what effect concessions will have, and if promises will be kept.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Thus there will be mistrust and unwillingness to make concessions if at least one of the parties in a dispute is a non-democracy.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] However, game theory predicts that two countries may still go to war even if their leaders are cognizant of the costs of fighting.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] War may result from asymmetric information; two countries may have incentives to mis-represent the amount of military resources they have on hand, rendering them unable to settle disputes agreeably without resorting to fighting.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Moreover, war may arise because of commitment problems: if two countries wish to settle a dispute via peaceful means, but each wishes to go back on the terms of that settlement, they may have no choice but to resort to warfare.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Finally, war may result from issue indivisibilities.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game theory could also help predict a nation's responses when there is a new rule or law to be applied to that nation.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] One example is Peter John Wood's (2013) research looking into what nations could do to help reduce climate change.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Wood thought this could be accomplished by making treaties with other nations to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] However, he concluded that this idea could not work because it would create a prisoner's dilemma for the nations.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game theory has been used extensively to model decision-making scenarios relevant to defence applications.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Most studies that have applied game theory in defence settings are concerned with Command and Control Warfare, and can be further classified into studies dealing with (i) Resource Allocation Warfare (ii) Information Warfare (iii) Weapons Control Warfare, and (iv) Adversary Monitoring Warfare.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The tool, for example, automates the transformation of public vulnerability data into models, allowing defenders to synthesize optimal defence strategies through Stackelberg equilibrium analysis.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] This approach enhances cyber resilience by enabling defenders to anticipate and counteract attackers’ best responses, making game theory increasingly relevant in adversarial cybersecurity environments.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Ho et al. provide a broad summary of game theory applications in defence, highlighting its advantages and limitations across both physical and cyber domains.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Unlike those in economics, the payoffs for games in biology are often interpreted as corresponding to fitness.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In addition, the focus has been less on equilibria that correspond to a notion of rationality and more on ones that would be maintained by evolutionary forces.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The best-known equilibrium in biology is known as the *evolutionarily stable strategy* (ESS), first introduced in (Maynard Smith & Price 1973).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Although its initial motivation did not involve any of the mental requirements of the Nash equilibrium, every ESS is a Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In biology, game theory has been used as a model to understand many different phenomena.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] It was first used to explain the evolution (and stability) of the approximate 1:1 sex ratios.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] (Fisher 1930) suggested that the 1:1 sex ratios are a result of evolutionary forces acting on individuals who could be seen as trying to maximize their number of grandchildren.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Additionally, biologists have used evolutionary game theory and the ESS to explain the emergence of animal communication.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The analysis of signaling games and other communication games has provided insight into the evolution of communication among animals.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] For example, the mobbing behavior of many species, in which a large number of prey animals attack a larger predator, seems to be an example of spontaneous emergent organization.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Ants have also been shown to exhibit feed-forward behavior akin to fashion (see Paul Ormerod's *Butterfly Economics*).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Biologists have used the game of chicken to analyze fighting behavior and territoriality.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] According to Maynard Smith, in the preface to *Evolution and the Theory of Games*, "paradoxically, it has turned out that game theory is more readily applied to biology than to the field of economic behaviour for which it was originally designed".
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Evolutionary game theory has been used to explain many seemingly incongruous phenomena in nature.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] One such phenomenon is known as biological altruism.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] This is a situation in which an organism appears to act in a way that benefits other organisms and is detrimental to itself.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] This is distinct from traditional notions of altruism because such actions are not conscious, but appear to be evolutionary adaptations to increase overall fitness.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] All of these actions increase the overall fitness of a group, but occur at a cost to the individual.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Evolutionary game theory explains this altruism with the idea of kin selection.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Altruists discriminate between the individuals they help and favor relatives.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Hamilton's rule explains the evolutionary rationale behind this selection with the equation c < b × r, where the cost *c* to the altruist must be less than the benefit *b* to the recipient multiplied by the coefficient of relatedness *r*.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The more closely related two organisms are causes the incidences of altruism to increase because they share many of the same alleles.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] This means that the altruistic individual, by ensuring that the alleles of its close relative are passed on through survival of its offspring, can forgo the option of having offspring itself because the same number of alleles are passed on.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] For example, helping a sibling (in diploid animals) has a coefficient of 1⁄2, because (on average) an individual shares half of the alleles in its sibling's offspring.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Ensuring that enough of a sibling's offspring survive to adulthood precludes the necessity of the altruistic individual producing offspring.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Similarly if it is considered that information other than that of a genetic nature (e.g. epigenetics, religion, science, etc.) persisted through time the playing field becomes larger still, and the discrepancies smaller.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game theory has come to play an increasingly important role in logic and in computer science.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Several logical theories have a basis in game semantics.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In addition, computer scientists have used games to model interactive computations.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Also, game theory provides a theoretical basis to the field of multi-agent systems.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Separately, game theory has played a role in online algorithms; in particular, the *k*-server problem, which has in the past been referred to as *games with moving costs* and *request-answer games*.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Yao's principle is a game-theoretic technique for proving lower bounds on the computational complexity of randomized algorithms, especially online algorithms.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The emergence of the Internet has motivated the development of algorithms for finding equilibria in games, markets, computational auctions, peer-to-peer systems, and security and information markets.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Algorithmic game theory and within it algorithmic mechanism design combine computational algorithm design and analysis of complex systems with economic theory.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game theory has multiple applications in the field of artificial intelligence and machine learning.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] It is often used in developing autonomous systems that can make complex decisions in uncertain environment.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Some other areas of application of game theory in AI/ML context are as follows - multi-agent system formation, reinforcement learning, mechanism design etc.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] By using game theory to model the behavior of other agents and anticipate their actions, AI/ML systems can make better decisions and operate more effectively.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game theory has been put to several uses in philosophy.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Quine (1960, 1967), Lewis (1969) used game theory to develop a philosophical account of convention.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In so doing, he provided the first analysis of common knowledge and employed it in analyzing play in coordination games.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In addition, he first suggested that one can understand meaning in terms of signaling games.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] This later suggestion has been pursued by several philosophers since Lewis.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Following Lewis (1969) game-theoretic account of conventions, Edna Ullmann-Margalit (1977) and Bicchieri (2006) have developed theories of social norms that define them as Nash equilibria that result from transforming a mixed-motive game into a coordination game.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Game theory has also challenged philosophers to think in terms of interactive epistemology: what it means for a collective to have common beliefs or knowledge, and what are the consequences of this knowledge for the social outcomes resulting from the interactions of agents.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Philosophers who have worked in this area include Bicchieri (1989, 1993), Skyrms (1990), and Stalnaker (1999).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The synthesis of game theory with ethics was championed by R.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The hope was that rigorous mathematical analysis of game theory might help formalize the more imprecise philosophical discussions.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] However, this expectation was only materialized to a limited extent.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In ethics, some (most notably David Gauthier, Gregory Kavka, and Jean Hampton) authors have attempted to pursue Thomas Hobbes' project of deriving morality from self-interest.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Since games like the prisoner's dilemma present an apparent conflict between morality and self-interest, explaining why cooperation is required by self-interest is an important component of this project.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] This general strategy is a component of the general social contract view in political philosophy (for examples, see Gauthier (1986) and Kavka (1986)).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Other authors have attempted to use evolutionary game theory in order to explain the emergence of human attitudes about morality and corresponding animal behaviors.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] These authors look at several games including the prisoner's dilemma, stag hunt, and the Nash bargaining game as providing an explanation for the emergence of attitudes about morality (see, e.g., Skyrms (1996, 2004) and Sober and Wilson (1998)).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Two members of a criminal gang, A and B, are arrested and imprisoned.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Each prisoner is in solitary confinement with no means of communication with their partner.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The principal charge would lead to a sentence of ten years in prison; however, the police do not have the evidence for a conviction.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The dominant strategy (and therefore the best response to any possible opponent strategy), is to betray the other, which aligns with the sure-thing principle.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] However, both prisoners staying silent would yield a greater reward for both of them than mutual betrayal.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The "battle of the sexes" is a term used to describe the perceived conflict between men and women in various areas of life, such as relationships, careers, and social roles.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] This conflict is often portrayed in popular culture, such as movies and television shows, as a humorous or dramatic competition between the genders.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] This conflict can be depicted in a game theory framework.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] This is an example of non-cooperative games.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] An example of the "battle of the sexes" can be seen in the portrayal of relationships in popular media, where men and women are often depicted as being fundamentally different and in conflict with each other.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] For instance, in some romantic comedies, the male and female protagonists are shown as having opposing views on love and relationships, and they have to overcome these differences in order to be together.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In this game, there are two pure strategy Nash equilibria: one where both the players choose some option and one where the players choose the other option.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] If the game is played in mixed strategies, where each player chooses their strategy randomly, then there is an infinite number of Nash equilibria.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] However, in the context of the "battle of the sexes" game, the assumption is usually made that the game is played in pure strategies.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The ultimatum game is a game that has become a popular instrument of economic experiments.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] An early description is by Nobel laureate John Harsanyi in 1961.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] One player, the proposer, is endowed with a sum of money.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The proposer is tasked with splitting it with another player, the responder (who knows what the total sum is).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Once the proposer communicates his decision, the responder may accept it or reject it.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] If the responder accepts, the money is split per the proposal; if the responder rejects, both players receive nothing.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Both players know in advance the consequences of the responder accepting or rejecting the offer.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The game demonstrates how social acceptance, fairness, and generosity influence the players decisions.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Ultimatum game has a variant, that is the dictator game.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] They are mostly identical, except in dictator game the responder has no power to reject the proposer's offer.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The Trust Game is an experiment designed to measure trust in economic decisions.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] It is also called "the investment game" and is designed to investigate trust and demonstrate its importance rather than "rationality" of self-interest.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The game was designed by Berg Joyce, John Dickhaut and Kevin McCabe in 1995.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In the game, one player (the investor) is given a sum of money and must decide how much of it to give to another player (the trustee).
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The amount given is then tripled by the experimenter.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The trustee then decides how much of the tripled amount to return to the investor.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] If the trustee is completely self-interested, then they would return nothing.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] However, experiments have shown that this isn't the expected behavior of the trustee.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The outcome instead suggests that people are willing to place trust, by risking some amount of money, in the belief that there will be reciprocity.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The Cournot competition model involves players choosing quantity of a homogenous product to produce independently and simultaneously, where marginal cost can be different for each firm and the firm's payoff is profit.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The production costs are public information and the firm aims to find their profit-maximizing quantity based on what they believe the other firm will produce and behave like monopolies.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] In this game firms want to produce at the monopoly quantity but there is a high incentive to deviate and produce more, which decreases the market-clearing price.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] For example, firms may be tempted to deviate from the monopoly quantity if there is a low monopoly quantity and high price, with the aim of increasing production to maximize profit.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] However this option does not provide the highest payoff, as a firm's ability to maximize profits depends on its market share and the elasticity of the market demand.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The Cournot equilibrium is reached when each firm operates on their reaction function with no incentive to deviate, as they have the best response based on the other firms output.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Within the game, firms reach the Nash equilibrium when the Cournot equilibrium is achieved.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The Bertrand competition assumes homogenous products and a constant marginal cost and players choose the prices.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] The equilibrium of price competition is where the price is equal to marginal costs, assuming complete information about the competitors' costs.
[src:game-theory/game-theory-p02] Therefore, the firms have an incentive to deviate from the equilibrium because a homogenous product with a lower price will gain all of the market share, known as a cost advantage.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The **maximin value** is the highest value that the player can be sure to get without knowing the actions of the other players; equivalently, it is the lowest value the other players can force the player to receive when they know the player's action.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Calculating the maximin value of a player is done in a worst-case approach: for each possible action of the player, we check all possible actions of the other players and determine the worst possible combination of actions – the one that gives player i the smallest value.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Then, we determine which action player i can take in order to make sure that this smallest value is the highest possible.
[src:game-theory/minimax] For example, consider the following game for two players, where the first player ("row player") may choose any of three moves, labelled T, M, or B, and the second player ("column player") may choose either of two moves, L or R.
[src:game-theory/minimax] (where the first number in each of the cell is the pay-out of the row player and the second number is the pay-out of the column player).
[src:game-theory/minimax] For the sake of example, we consider only pure strategies.
[src:game-theory/minimax] If both players play their respective maximin strategies $(T,L)$ , the payoff vector is $(3,1)$ .
[src:game-theory/minimax] The **minimax value** of a player is the smallest value that the other players can force the player to receive, without knowing the player's actions; equivalently, it is the largest value the player can be sure to get when they *know* the actions of the other players.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The definition is very similar to that of the maximin value – only the order of the maximum and minimum operators is inverse.
[src:game-theory/minimax] In two-player zero-sum games, the minimax solution is the same as the Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Equivalently, Player 1's strategy guarantees them a payoff of V regardless of Player 2's strategy, and similarly Player 2 can guarantee themselves a payoff of −V.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The name *minimax* arises because each player minimizes the maximum payoff possible for the other – since the game is zero-sum, they also minimize their own maximum loss (i.e., maximize their minimum payoff).
[src:game-theory/minimax] See also example of a game without a value.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The following example of a zero-sum game, where **A** and **B** make simultaneous moves, illustrates *maximin* solutions.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Suppose each player has three choices and consider the payoff matrix for **A** displayed on the table ("Payoff matrix for player A").
[src:game-theory/minimax] Assume the payoff matrix for **B** is the same matrix with the signs reversed (i.e., if the choices are A1 and B1 then **B** pays 3 to **A**).
[src:game-theory/minimax] Then, the maximin choice for **A** is A2 since the worst possible result is then having to pay 1, while the simple maximin choice for **B** is B2 since the worst possible result is then no payment.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Some choices are *dominated* by others and can be eliminated: **A** will not choose A3 since either A1 or A2 will produce a better result, no matter what **B** chooses; **B** will not choose B3 since some mixtures of B1 and B2 will produce a better result, no matter what **A** chooses.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Similarly, **B** can ensure an expected gain of at least ⁠1/ 3 ⁠, no matter what **A** chooses, by using a randomized strategy of choosing B1 with probability ⁠1/ 3 ⁠ and B2 with probability ⁠2/ 3 ⁠.
[src:game-theory/minimax] These mixed minimax strategies cannot be improved and are now stable.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Frequently, in game theory, **maximin** is distinct from minimax.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Minimax is used in zero-sum games to denote minimizing the opponent's maximum payoff.
[src:game-theory/minimax] In a zero-sum game, this is identical to minimizing one's own maximum loss, and to maximizing one's own minimum gain.
[src:game-theory/minimax] "Maximin" is a term commonly used for non-zero-sum games to describe the strategy which maximizes one's own minimum payoff.
[src:game-theory/minimax] In non-zero-sum games, this is not generally the same as minimizing the opponent's maximum gain, nor the same as the Nash equilibrium strategy.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The minimax values are very important in the theory of repeated games.
[src:game-theory/minimax] One of the central theorems in this theory, the folk theorem, relies on the minimax values.
[src:game-theory/minimax] In combinatorial game theory, there is a minimax algorithm for game solutions.
[src:game-theory/minimax] A **simple** version of the minimax *algorithm*, stated below, deals with games such as tic-tac-toe, where each player can win, lose, or draw.
[src:game-theory/minimax] If player A *can* win in one move, their best move is that winning move.
[src:game-theory/minimax] If player B knows that one move will lead to the situation where player A *can* win in one move, while another move will lead to the situation where player A can, at best, draw, then player B's best move is the one leading to a draw.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Late in the game, it's easy to see what the "best" move is.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The minimax algorithm helps find the best move, by working backwards from the end of the game.
[src:game-theory/minimax] At each step it assumes that player A is trying to **maximize** the chances of A winning, while on the next turn player B is trying to **minimize** the chances of A winning (i.e., to maximize B's own chances of winning).
[src:game-theory/minimax] A **minimax algorithm** is a recursive algorithm for choosing the next move in an n-player game, usually a two-player game.
[src:game-theory/minimax] A value is associated with each position or state of the game.
[src:game-theory/minimax] This value is computed by means of a position evaluation function and it indicates how good it would be for a player to reach that position.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The player then makes the move that maximizes the minimum value of the position resulting from the opponent's possible following moves.
[src:game-theory/minimax] If it is **A**'s turn to move, **A** gives a value to each of their legal moves.
[src:game-theory/minimax] A possible allocation method consists in assigning a certain win for **A** as +1 and for **B** as −1.
[src:game-theory/minimax] This leads to combinatorial game theory as developed by John H.
[src:game-theory/minimax] An alternative is using a rule that if the result of a move is an immediate win for **A**, it is assigned positive infinity and if it is an immediate win for **B**, negative infinity.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The value to **A** of any other move is the maximum of the values resulting from each of **B**'s possible replies.
[src:game-theory/minimax] For this reason, **A** is called the *maximizing player* and **B** is called the *minimizing player*, hence the name *minimax algorithm*.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The above algorithm will assign a value of positive or negative infinity to any position since the value of every position will be the value of some final winning or losing position.
[src:game-theory/minimax] This can be extended if we can supply a heuristic evaluation function which gives values to non-final game states without considering all possible following complete sequences.
[src:game-theory/minimax] We can then limit the minimax algorithm to look only at a certain number of moves ahead.
[src:game-theory/minimax] This number is called the "look-ahead", measured in "plies".
[src:game-theory/minimax] For example, the chess computer Deep Blue (the first one to beat a reigning world champion, Garry Kasparov at that time) looked ahead at least 12 plies, then applied a heuristic evaluation function.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The algorithm can be thought of as exploring the nodes of a *game tree*.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The *effective branching factor* of the tree is the average number of children of each node (i.e., the average number of legal moves in a position).
[src:game-theory/minimax] The number of nodes to be explored usually increases exponentially with the number of plies (it is less than exponential if evaluating forced moves or repeated positions).
[src:game-theory/minimax] The number of nodes to be explored for the analysis of a game is therefore approximately the branching factor raised to the power of the number of plies.
[src:game-theory/minimax] It is therefore impractical to completely analyze games such as chess using the minimax algorithm.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The performance of the naïve minimax algorithm may be improved dramatically, without affecting the result, by the use of alpha–beta pruning.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Other heuristic pruning methods can also be used, but not all of them are guaranteed to give the same result as the unpruned search.
[src:game-theory/minimax] A naïve minimax algorithm may be trivially modified to additionally return an entire Principal Variation along with a minimax score.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The pseudocode for the depth-limited minimax algorithm is given below.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The minimax function returns a heuristic value for leaf nodes (terminal nodes and nodes at the maximum search depth).
[src:game-theory/minimax] Non-leaf nodes inherit their value from a descendant leaf node.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The heuristic value is a score measuring the favorability of the node for the maximizing player.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Hence nodes resulting in a favorable outcome, such as a win, for the maximizing player have higher scores than nodes more favorable for the minimizing player.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The heuristic value for terminal (game ending) leaf nodes are scores corresponding to win, loss, or draw, for the maximizing player.
[src:game-theory/minimax] For non terminal leaf nodes at the maximum search depth, an evaluation function estimates a heuristic value for the node.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The quality of this estimate and the search depth determine the quality and accuracy of the final minimax result.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Minimax treats the two players (the maximizing player and the minimizing player) separately in its code.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Based on the observation that $\ \max(a,b)=-\min(-a,-b)\ ,$ minimax may often be simplified into the negamax algorithm.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Suppose the game being played only has a maximum of two possible moves per player each turn.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The algorithm generates the tree on the right, where the circles represent the moves of the player running the algorithm (*maximizing player*), and squares represent the moves of the opponent (*minimizing player*).
[src:game-theory/minimax] Because of the limitation of computation resources, as explained above, the tree is limited to a *look-ahead* of 4 moves.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The algorithm evaluates each *leaf node* using a heuristic evaluation function, obtaining the values shown.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The moves where the *maximizing player* wins are assigned with positive infinity, while the moves that lead to a win of the *minimizing player* are assigned with negative infinity.
[src:game-theory/minimax] At level 3, the algorithm will choose, for each node, the **smallest** of the *child node* values, and assign it to that same node (e.g. the node on the left will choose the minimum between "10" and "+∞", therefore assigning the value "10" to itself).
[src:game-theory/minimax] The next step, in level 2, consists of choosing for each node the **largest** of the *child node* values.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Once again, the values are assigned to each *parent node*.
[src:game-theory/minimax] The algorithm continues evaluating the maximum and minimum values of the child nodes alternately until it reaches the *root node*, where it chooses the move with the largest value (represented in the figure with a blue arrow).
[src:game-theory/minimax] This is the move that the player should make in order to *minimize* the *maximum* possible loss.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Minimax theory has been extended to decisions where there is no other player, but where the consequences of decisions depend on unknown facts.
[src:game-theory/minimax] For example, deciding to prospect for minerals entails a cost, which will be wasted if the minerals are not present, but will bring major rewards if they are.
[src:game-theory/minimax] One approach is to treat this as a game against *nature* (see move by nature), and using a similar mindset as Murphy's law or resistentialism, take an approach which minimizes the maximum expected loss, using the same techniques as in the two-person zero-sum games.
[src:game-theory/minimax] In addition, expectiminimax trees have been developed, for two-player games in which chance (for example, dice) is a factor.
[src:game-theory/minimax] In classical statistical decision theory, we have an estimator $\ \delta \$ that is used to estimate a parameter $\ \theta \in \Theta \ .$ We also assume a risk function $\ R(\theta ,\delta )\ .$ usually specified as the integral of a loss function.
[src:game-theory/minimax] A key feature of minimax decision making is being non-probabilistic: in contrast to decisions using expected value or expected utility, it makes no assumptions about the probabilities of various outcomes, just scenario analysis of what the possible outcomes are.
[src:game-theory/minimax] It is thus robust to changes in the assumptions, in contrast to these other decision techniques.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Various extensions of this non-probabilistic approach exist, notably minimax regret and Info-gap decision theory.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Compare to expected value analysis, whose conclusion is of the form: "This strategy yields ℰ(X) = n ." Minimax thus can be used on ordinal data, and can be more transparent.
[src:game-theory/minimax] In philosophy, the term "maximin" is often used in the context of John Rawls's *A Theory of Justice,* where he refers to it in the context of The Difference Principle.
[src:game-theory/minimax] Rawls defined this principle as the rule which states that social and economic inequalities should be arranged so that "they are to be of the greatest benefit to the least-advantaged members of society".
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In game theory, a **Nash equilibrium** is a situation where no player could gain more by changing their own strategy (holding all other players' strategies fixed) in a game.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] A Nash equilibrium is the most commonly used solution concept for non-cooperative games.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In a game in which Carol and Dan are also players, (A, B, C, D) is a Nash equilibrium if A is Alice's best response to (B, C, D), B is Bob's best response to (A, C, D), and so forth.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The concept of a Nash equilibrium dates back to the time of Cournot, who in 1838 applied it to his model of competition in an oligopoly.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] John Nash showed that there is a Nash equilibrium, possibly in mixed strategies, for every finite game.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Game theorists use Nash equilibrium to analyze the outcome of the strategic interaction of several decision makers.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In a strategic interaction, the outcome for each decision-maker depends on the decisions of the others as well as their own.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The insight underlying Nash's idea is that one cannot predict the choices of multiple decision makers if one analyzes those decisions in isolation.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Instead, one must ask what each player would do taking into account what the player expects the others to do.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] A Nash equilibrium is achieved when no player can improve their outcome by changing their decision, assuming the other players' choices remain unchanged.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The concept has been used to analyze hostile situations such as wars and arms races (see prisoner's dilemma), and also how conflict may be mitigated by repeated interaction (see tit-for-tat).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] It has also been used to study to what extent people with different preferences can cooperate (see battle of the sexes), and whether they will take risks to achieve a cooperative outcome (see stag hunt).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] It has been used to study the adoption of technical standards, and also the occurrence of bank runs and currency crises (see coordination game).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Nash equilibrium is named after American mathematician John Forbes Nash Jr.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The same idea was used in a particular application in 1838 by Antoine Augustin Cournot in his theory of oligopoly.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In Cournot's theory, each of several firms choose how much output to produce to maximize its profit.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The best output for one firm depends on the outputs of the others.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] A Cournot equilibrium occurs when each firm's output maximizes its profits given the output of the other firms, which is a pure-strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Cournot also introduced the concept of best response dynamics in his analysis of the stability of equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Cournot did not use the idea in any other applications, however, or define it generally.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The modern concept of Nash equilibrium is instead defined in terms of mixed strategies, where players choose a probability distribution over possible pure strategies (which might put 100% of the probability on one pure strategy; such pure strategies are a subset of mixed strategies).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The concept of a mixed-strategy equilibrium was introduced by John von Neumann and Oskar Morgenstern in their 1944 book *The Theory of Games and Economic Behavior*, but their analysis was restricted to the special case of zero-sum games.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] They showed that a mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium will exist for any zero-sum game with a finite set of actions.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The contribution of Nash in his 1951 article "Non-Cooperative Games" was to define a mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium for any game with a finite set of actions and prove that at least one (mixed-strategy) Nash equilibrium must exist in such a game.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The key to Nash's ability to prove existence far more generally than von Neumann lay in his definition of equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] According to Nash, "an equilibrium point is an n-tuple such that each player's mixed strategy maximizes [their] payoff if the strategies of the others are held fixed.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Thus each player's strategy is optimal against those of the others." Putting the problem in this framework allowed Nash to employ the Kakutani fixed-point theorem in his 1950 paper to prove existence of equilibria.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] His 1951 paper used the simpler Brouwer fixed-point theorem for the same purpose.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Game theorists have discovered that in some circumstances Nash equilibrium makes invalid predictions or fails to make a unique prediction.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] They have proposed many solution concepts ('refinements' of Nash equilibria) designed to rule out implausible Nash equilibria.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] One particularly important issue is that some Nash equilibria may be based on threats that are not 'credible'.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In 1965 Reinhard Selten proposed subgame perfect equilibrium as a refinement that eliminates equilibria which depend on non-credible threats.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Other extensions of the Nash equilibrium concept have addressed what happens if a game is repeated, or what happens if a game is played in the absence of complete information.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] However, subsequent refinements and extensions of Nash equilibrium share the main insight on which Nash's concept rests: the equilibrium is a set of strategies such that each player's strategy is optimal given the choices of the others.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] A strategy profile is a set of strategies, one for each player.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Informally, a strategy profile is a Nash equilibrium if no player can do better by unilaterally changing their strategy.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] To see what this means, imagine that each player is told the strategies of the others.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] For instance if a player prefers "Yes", then that set of strategies is not a Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] But if every player prefers not to switch (or is indifferent between switching and not) then the strategy profile is a Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Thus, each strategy in a Nash equilibrium is a best response to the other players' strategies in that equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Formally, let $S_{i}$ be the set of all possible strategies for player i , where $i=1,\ldots ,N$ .
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Let $s^{*}=(s_{i}^{*},s_{-i}^{*})$ be a strategy profile, a set consisting of one strategy for each player, where $s_{-i}^{*}$ denotes the $N-1$ strategies of all the players except i .
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Let $u_{i}(s_{i},s_{-i}^{*})$ be player *i*'s payoff as a function of the strategies.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] A game can have more than one Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Even if the equilibrium is unique, it might be *weak*: a player might be indifferent among several strategies given the other players' choices.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The strategy set $S_{i}$ can be different for different players, and its elements can be a variety of mathematical objects.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Nash's existence proofs assume a finite strategy set, but the concept of Nash equilibrium does not require it.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] A game can have a pure-strategy or a mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In the latter, not every player always plays the same strategy.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Instead, there is a probability distribution over different strategies.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If every player's answer is "Yes", then the equilibrium is classified as a *strict Nash equilibrium*.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If instead, for some player, there is exact equality between the strategy in Nash equilibrium and some other strategy that gives exactly the same payout (i.e., the player is indifferent between switching and not), then the equilibrium is classified as a *weak* or *non-strict Nash equilibrium*.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The Nash equilibrium defines stability only in terms of individual player deviations.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In cooperative games such a concept is not convincing enough.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Strong Nash equilibrium allows for deviations by every conceivable coalition.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Formally, a strong Nash equilibrium is a Nash equilibrium in which no coalition, taking the actions of its complements as given, can cooperatively deviate in a way that benefits all of its members.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] However, the strong Nash concept is sometimes perceived as too "strong" in that the environment allows for unlimited private communication.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In fact, strong Nash equilibrium has to be weakly Pareto efficient.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] As a result of these requirements, strong Nash is too rare to be useful in many branches of game theory.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] However, in games such as elections with many more players than possible outcomes, it can be more common than a stable equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] A refined Nash equilibrium known as coalition-proof Nash equilibrium (CPNE) occurs when players cannot do better even if they are allowed to communicate and make "self-enforcing" agreement to deviate.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Every correlated strategy supported by iterated strict dominance and on the Pareto frontier is a CPNE.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Further, it is possible for a game to have a Nash equilibrium that is resilient against coalitions less than a specified size, k.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] CPNE is related to the theory of the core.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Nash equilibria need not exist if the set of choices is infinite and non-compact.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] However, a Nash equilibrium exists if the set of choices is compact with each player's payoff continuous in the strategies of all the players.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Nash's existence theorem has been extended to more general classes of games.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In Nash's model, the set of strategies available to each player is fixed and does not depend on the other players' strategies.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] A more general model allows these sets to depend on other players' strategies; this is often called **coupled constraints**.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In Nash's model, the set of possible strategy-profiles is a Cartesian product of the players' strategy sets, whereas in the more general model it can be an arbitrary set.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] When there are coupled constraints, the equilibrium is often called **Generalized Nash equilibrium** **(GNE)**.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Rosen proved that, if the set of strategy-profiles is any convex set, and the utility function of each player is continuous in all strategies and a concave function of the player's own strategy, then a GNE exists; see **concave games**.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Nash considered games with finitely many players, in **non-atomic games** the set of players is infinite - there is a continuum of players David Schmeidler proved that an equilibrium exists under certain conditions.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The Nash equilibrium may sometimes appear non-rational in a third-person perspective.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This is because a Nash equilibrium is not necessarily Pareto optimal.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Nash equilibrium may also have non-rational consequences in sequential games because players may "threaten" each other with threats they would not actually carry out.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] For such games the subgame perfect Nash equilibrium may be more meaningful as a tool of analysis.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The *coordination game* is a classic two-player, two-strategy game, as shown in the example payoff matrix to the right.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] There are two pure-strategy equilibria, (A,A) with payoff 4 for each player and (B,B) with payoff 2 for each.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The combination (B,B) is a Nash equilibrium because if either player unilaterally changes their strategy from B to A, their payoff will fall from 2 to 1.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] A famous example of a coordination game is the stag hunt.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Two players may choose to hunt a stag or a rabbit, the stag providing more meat (4 utility units, 2 for each player) than the rabbit (1 utility unit).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The caveat is that the stag must be cooperatively hunted, so if one player attempts to hunt the stag, while the other hunts the rabbit, the stag hunter will totally fail, for a payoff of 0, whereas the rabbit hunter will succeed, for a payoff of 1.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The game has two equilibria, (stag, stag) and (rabbit, rabbit), because a player's optimal strategy depends on their expectation on what the other player will do.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If one hunter trusts that the other will hunt the stag, they should hunt the stag; however if they think the other will hunt the rabbit, they too will hunt the rabbit.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This game is used as an analogy for social cooperation, since much of the benefit that people gain in society depends upon people cooperating and implicitly trusting one another to act in a manner corresponding with cooperation.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Driving on a road against an oncoming car, and having to choose either to swerve on the left or to swerve on the right of the road, is also a coordination game.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In this case there are two pure-strategy Nash equilibria, when both choose to either drive on the left or on the right.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] We add another where the probabilities for each player are (50%, 50%).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] An application of Nash equilibria is in determining the expected flow of traffic in a network.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If we assume that there are x "cars" traveling from A to D, what is the expected distribution of traffic in the network?
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This situation can be modeled as a "game", where every traveler has a choice of 3 strategies and where each strategy is a route from A to D (one of ABD, ABCD, or ACD).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The "payoff" of each strategy is the travel time of each route.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In the graph on the right, a car travelling via ABD experiences travel time of $1+{\frac {x}{100}}+2$ , where x is the number of cars traveling on edge AB.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Thus, payoffs for any given strategy depend on the choices of the other players, as is usual.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] However, the goal, in this case, is to minimize travel time, not maximize it.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Equilibrium will occur when the time on all paths is exactly the same.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] When that happens, no single driver has any incentive to switch routes, since it can only add to their travel time.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] For the graph on the right, if, for example, 100 cars are travelling from A to D, then equilibrium will occur when 25 drivers travel via ABD, 50 via ABCD, and 25 via ACD.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Every driver now has a total travel time of 3.75 (to see this, a total of 75 cars take the AB edge, and likewise, 75 cars take the CD edge).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Notice that this distribution is not, actually, socially optimal.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If the 100 cars agreed that 50 travel via ABD and the other 50 through ACD, then travel time for any single car would actually be 3.5, which is less than 3.75.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This is also the Nash equilibrium if the path between B and C is removed, which means that adding another possible route can decrease the efficiency of the system, a phenomenon known as Braess's paradox.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This can be illustrated by a two-player game in which both players simultaneously choose an integer from 0 to 3 and they both win the smaller of the two numbers in points.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In addition, if one player chooses a larger number than the other, then they have to give up two points to the other.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This game has a unique pure-strategy Nash equilibrium: both players choosing 0 (highlighted in light red).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Any other strategy can be improved by a player switching their number to one less than that of the other player.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In the adjacent table, if the game begins at the green square, it is in player 1's interest to move to the purple square and it is in player 2's interest to move to the blue square.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Although it would not fit the definition of a competition game, if the game is modified so that the two players win the named amount if they both choose the same number, and otherwise win nothing, then there are 4 Nash equilibria: (0,0), (1,1), (2,2), and (3,3).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] There is an easy numerical way to identify Nash equilibria on a payoff matrix.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] It is especially helpful in two-person games where players have more than two strategies.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In this case formal analysis may become too long.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This rule does not apply to the case where mixed (stochastic) strategies are of interest.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The rule goes as follows: if the first payoff number, in the payoff pair of the cell, is the maximum of the column of the cell and if the second number is the maximum of the row of the cell – then the cell represents a Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Using the rule, we can very quickly (much faster than with formal analysis) see that the Nash equilibria cells are (B,A), (A,B), and (C,C).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Indeed, for cell (B,A), 40 is the maximum of the first column and 25 is the maximum of the second row.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] For (A,B), 25 is the maximum of the second column and 40 is the maximum of the first row; the same applies for cell (C,C).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] For other cells, either one or both of the duplet members are not the maximum of the corresponding rows and columns.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This said, the actual mechanics of finding equilibrium cells is obvious: find the maximum of a column and check if the second member of the pair is the maximum of the row.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If these conditions are met, the cell represents a Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Check all columns this way to find all NE cells.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] An N×N matrix may have between 0 and N×N pure-strategy Nash equilibria.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The concept of stability, useful in the analysis of many kinds of equilibria, can also be applied to Nash equilibria.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] 2. the player who did change is now playing with a strictly worse strategy.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If these cases are both met, then a player with the small change in their mixed strategy will return immediately to the Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If condition one does not hold then the equilibrium is unstable.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If only condition one holds then there are likely to be an infinite number of optimal strategies for the player who changed.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In the "driving game" example above there are both stable and unstable equilibria.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The equilibria involving mixed strategies with 100% probabilities are stable.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If either player changes their probabilities slightly, they will be both at a disadvantage, and their opponent will have no reason to change their strategy in turn.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If either player changes their probabilities (which would neither benefit or damage the expectation of the player who did the change, if the other player's mixed strategy is still (50%,50%)), then the other player immediately has a better strategy at either (0%, 100%) or (100%, 0%).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Stability is crucial in practical applications of Nash equilibria, since the mixed strategy of each player is not perfectly known, but has to be inferred from statistical distribution of their actions in the game.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In this case unstable equilibria are very unlikely to arise in practice, since any minute change in the proportions of each strategy seen will lead to a change in strategy and the breakdown of the equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Finally in the eighties, building with great depth on such ideas Mertens-stable equilibria were introduced as a solution concept.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Mertens stable equilibria satisfy both forward induction and backward induction.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In a game theory context stable equilibria now usually refer to Mertens stable equilibria.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If a game has a unique Nash equilibrium and is played among players under certain conditions, then the NE strategy set will be adopted.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The players have sufficient intelligence to deduce the solution.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The players know the planned equilibrium strategy of all of the other players.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The players believe that a deviation in their own strategy will not cause deviations by any other players.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] There is common knowledge that all players meet these conditions, including this one.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] So, not only must each player know the other players meet the conditions, but also they must know that they all know that they meet them, and know that they know that they know that they meet them, and so on.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Intentional or accidental imperfection in execution.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] For example, a computer capable of flawless logical play facing a second flawless computer will result in equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Introduction of imperfection will lead to its disruption either through loss to the player who makes the mistake, or through negation of the common knowledge criterion leading to possible victory for the player.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] (An example would be a player suddenly putting the car into reverse in the game of chicken, ensuring a no-loss no-win scenario).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In many cases, the third condition is not met because, even though the equilibrium must exist, it is unknown due to the complexity of the game, for instance in Chinese chess.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Or, if known, it may not be known to all players, as when playing tic-tac-toe with a small child who desperately wants to win (meeting the other criteria).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The criterion of common knowledge may not be met even if all players do, in fact, meet all the other criteria.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Players wrongly distrusting each other's rationality may adopt counter-strategies to expected irrational play on their opponents’ behalf.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This is a major consideration in "chicken" or an arms race, for example.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In his Ph.D. dissertation, John Nash proposed two interpretations of his equilibrium concept, with the objective of showing how equilibrium points can be connected with observable phenomena.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In this case, the conjectures need only be mutually known).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] For a formal result along these lines, see Kuhn, H. and et al., 1996, "The Work of John Nash in Game Theory", *Journal of Economic Theory*, 69, 153–185.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Due to the limited conditions in which NE can actually be observed, they are rarely treated as a guide to day-to-day behaviour, or observed in practice in human negotiations.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] However, as a theoretical concept in economics and evolutionary biology, the NE has explanatory power.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The payoff in economics is utility (or sometimes money), and in evolutionary biology is gene transmission; both are the fundamental bottom line of survival.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Researchers who apply games theory in these fields claim that strategies failing to maximize these for whatever reason will be competed out of the market or environment, which are ascribed the ability to test all strategies.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This conclusion is drawn from the "stability" theory above.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In these situations the assumption that the strategy observed is actually a NE has often been borne out by research.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The Nash equilibrium is a superset of the subgame perfect Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The subgame perfect equilibrium in addition to the Nash equilibrium requires that the strategy also is a Nash equilibrium in every subgame of that game.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This eliminates all non-credible threats, that is, strategies that contain non-rational moves in order to make the counter-player change their strategy.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The image to the right shows a simple sequential game that illustrates the issue with subgame imperfect Nash equilibria.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In this game player one chooses left(L) or right(R), which is followed by player two being called upon to be kind (K) or unkind (U) to player one, However, player two only stands to gain from being unkind if player one goes left.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If player one goes right the rational player two would de facto be kind to her/him in that subgame.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] However, The non-credible threat of being unkind at 2(2) is still part of the blue (L, (U,U)) Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Therefore, if rational behavior can be expected by both parties the subgame perfect Nash equilibrium may be a more meaningful solution concept when such dynamic inconsistencies arise.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Nash's original proof (in his thesis) used Brouwer's fixed-point theorem (e.g., see below for a variant).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This section presents a simpler proof via the Kakutani fixed-point theorem, following Nash's 1950 paper (he credits David Gale with the observation that such a simplification is possible).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Here, $\sigma \in \Sigma$ , where $\Sigma =\Sigma _{i}\times \Sigma _{-i}$ , is a mixed-strategy profile in the set of all mixed strategies and $u_{i}$ is the payoff function for player i.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Define a set-valued function $r\colon \Sigma \rightarrow 2^{\Sigma }$ such that $r=r_{i}(\sigma _{-i})\times r_{-i}(\sigma _{i})$ .
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The existence of a Nash equilibrium is equivalent to r having a fixed point.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Kakutani's fixed point theorem guarantees the existence of a fixed point if the following four conditions are satisfied.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Condition 1. is satisfied from the fact that $\Sigma$ is a simplex and thus compact.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Convexity follows from players' ability to mix strategies. $\Sigma$ is nonempty as long as players have strategies.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Condition 2. and 3. are satisfied by way of Berge's maximum theorem.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Because $u_{i}$ is continuous and compact, $r(\sigma _{i})$ is non-empty and upper hemicontinuous.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Condition 4. is satisfied as a result of mixed strategies.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Suppose $\sigma _{i},\sigma '_{i}\in r(\sigma _{-i})$ , then $\lambda \sigma _{i}+(1-\lambda )\sigma '_{i}\in r(\sigma _{-i})$ . i.e. if two strategies maximize payoffs, then a mix between the two strategies will yield the same payoff.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Therefore, there exists a fixed point in r and a Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] When Nash made this point to John von Neumann in 1949, von Neumann famously dismissed it with the words, "That's trivial, you know.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] That's just a fixed-point theorem." (See Nasar, 1998, p.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] We have a game $G=(N,A,u)$ where N is the number of players and $A=A_{1}\times \cdots \times A_{N}$ is the action set for the players.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] All of the action sets $A_{i}$ are finite.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Let $\Delta =\Delta _{1}\times \cdots \times \Delta _{N}$ denote the set of mixed strategies for the players.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The finiteness of the $A_{i}$ s ensures the compactness of $\Delta$ .
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The gain function represents the benefit a player gets by unilaterally changing their strategy.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] It is easy to see that each $f_{i}$ is a valid mixed strategy in $\Delta _{i}$ .
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] It is also easy to check that each $f_{i}$ is a continuous function of $\sigma$ , and hence f is a continuous function.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] As the cross product of a finite number of compact convex sets, $\Delta$ is also compact and convex.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Applying the Brouwer fixed point theorem to f and $\Delta$ we conclude that f has a fixed point in $\Delta$ , call it $\sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] We claim that $\sigma ^{*}$ is a Nash equilibrium in G .
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This simply states that each player gains no benefit by unilaterally changing their strategy, which is exactly the necessary condition for a Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Now assume that the gains are not all zero.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Also we shall denote ${\text{Gain}}(i,\cdot )$ as the gain vector indexed by actions in $A_{i}$ .
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Since $C>1$ we have that $\sigma _{i}^{*}$ is some positive scaling of the vector ${\text{Gain}}_{i}(\sigma ^{*},\cdot )$ .
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] To see this, first if ${\text{Gain}}_{i}(\sigma ^{*},a)>0$ then this is true by definition of the gain function.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] and so the left term is zero, giving us that the entire expression is 0 as needed.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] where the last inequality follows since $\sigma _{i}^{*}$ is a non-zero vector.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] But this is a clear contradiction, so all the gains must indeed be zero.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Therefore, $\sigma ^{*}$ is a Nash equilibrium for G as needed.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If a player A has a dominant strategy $s_{A}$ then there exists a Nash equilibrium in which A plays $s_{A}$ .
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In the case of two players A and B, there exists a Nash equilibrium in which A plays $s_{A}$ and B plays a best response to $s_{A}$ .
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If $s_{A}$ is a strictly dominant strategy, A plays $s_{A}$ in all Nash equilibria.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] If both A and B have strictly dominant strategies, there exists a unique Nash equilibrium in which each plays their strictly dominant strategy.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In games with mixed-strategy Nash equilibria, the probability of a player choosing any particular (so pure) strategy can be computed by assigning a variable to each strategy that represents a fixed probability for choosing that strategy.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In order for a player to be willing to randomize, their expected payoff for each (pure) strategy should be the same.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In addition, the sum of the probabilities for each strategy of a particular player should be 1.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] This creates a system of equations from which the probabilities of choosing each strategy can be derived.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In the matching pennies game, player A loses a point to B if A and B play the same strategy and wins a point from B if they play different strategies.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] To compute the mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium, assign A the probability p of playing H and $(1-p)$ of playing T, and assign B the probability q of playing H and $(1-q)$ of playing T.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Thus, a mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium in this game is for each player to randomly choose H or T with $p={\frac {1}{2}}$ and $q={\frac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In 1971, Robert Wilson came up with the "oddness theorem", which says that "almost all" finite games have a finite and odd number of Nash equilibria.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In 1973, Harsanyi published an alternative proof of the result.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] "Almost all" here means that any game with an infinite or even number of equilibria is very special in the sense that if its payoffs were even slightly randomly perturbed, with probability one it would have an odd number of equilibria instead.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The prisoner's dilemma, for example, has one equilibrium, while the battle of the sexes has three—two pure and one mixed, and this remains true even if the payoffs change slightly.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] The free money game is an example of a "special" game with an even number of equilibria.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In it, two players have to both vote "yes" rather than "no" to get a reward and the votes are simultaneous.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] There are two pure-strategy Nash equilibria, (yes, yes) and (no, no), and no mixed strategy equilibria, because the strategy "yes" weakly dominates "no".
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] "Yes" is as good as "no" regardless of the other player's action, but if there is any chance the other player chooses "yes" then "yes" is the best reply.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Under a small random perturbation of the payoffs, however, the probability that any two payoffs would remain tied, whether at 0 or some other number, is vanishingly small, and the game would have either one or three equilibria instead.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In 1950 Nash proved that every n -person normal form game has a Nash equilibrium (NE) in mixed strategies.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Yet, there are large families of games that have NE in pure strategies, for example, finite n -person positional (graphical) games with perfect information.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] In case of two players, Nash solvability in pure strategies is equivalent to duality of hypergraphs.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Later this result was extended for the non-zero sum case.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Interestingly, in such NE the strategy of one player doesn't depend on the preferences of the other.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] But the opposite is not necessarily true.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] One can check all 4 pure-strategy profiles (the 4 cells in the matrix), and verify that in all of them, one of the players has a profitable deviation, so there is no Nash equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] On the other hand, the minimax value of the row player is 1 (R-T) and the minimax value of the column player is 1 (B-R).
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] Hence, the strategy profile R-T is minmax-acceptable.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] There are games in which even a minmax-acceptable strategy profile does not exist.
[src:game-theory/nash-equilibrium] For example, in Matching pennies, the minimax values (with pure strategies) are 1,1, but the sum of payments is 0, so no strategy profile can give 1 to both players.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In game theory, the **prisoner's dilemma** is a thought experiment involving two rational agents, each of whom can either cooperate for mutual benefit or betray their partner ("defect") for individual gain.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The dilemma arises from the fact that while defecting is rational for each agent, cooperation yields a higher payoff for each.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The puzzle was designed by Merrill Flood and Melvin Dresher in 1950 during their work at the RAND Corporation.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] They invited economist Armen Alchian and mathematician John Williams to play a hundred rounds of the game, observing that Alchian and Williams often chose to cooperate.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] When asked about the results, John Nash remarked that rational behavior in the iterated version of the game can differ from that in a single-round version.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] This insight anticipated a key result in game theory: cooperation can emerge in repeated interactions, even in situations where it is not rational in a one-off interaction.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Tucker later named the game the "prisoner's dilemma" by framing the rewards in terms of prison sentences.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The prisoner's dilemma models many real-world situations involving strategic behavior.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In casual usage, the label "prisoner's dilemma" is applied to any situation in which two entities can gain important benefits by cooperating or suffer by failing to do so, but find it difficult or expensive to coordinate their choices.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If one testifies against the other but the other does not, the one testifying will be set free while the other serves three years in prison.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If A and B testify against each other, they will each serve two years.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Two prisoners are separated into individual rooms and cannot communicate with each other.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] It is assumed that both prisoners understand the nature of the game, have no loyalty to each other, and will have no opportunity for retribution or reward outside of the game.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Regardless of what the other decides, each prisoner gets a higher reward by betraying the other ("defecting").
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The reasoning involves analyzing both players' best responses: B will either cooperate or defect.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If B cooperates, A should defect, because going free is better than serving 1 year.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If B defects, A should also defect, because serving 2 years is better than serving 3.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] So, either way, A should defect since defecting is A's best response regardless of B's strategy.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Parallel reasoning will show that B should defect.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Defection always results in a better payoff than cooperation, so it is a strictly dominant strategy for both players.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Mutual defection is the only strong Nash equilibrium in the game.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Since the collectively ideal result of mutual cooperation is irrational from a self-interested standpoint, this Nash equilibrium is not Pareto efficient.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The structure of the traditional prisoner's dilemma can be generalized from its original prisoner setting.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Suppose that the two players are represented by the colors red and blue and that each player chooses to either "cooperate" or "defect".
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If both players cooperate, they both receive the reward R for cooperating.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If both players defect, they both receive the punishment payoff P .
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If Blue defects while Red cooperates, then Blue receives the temptation payoff T , while Red receives the "sucker's" payoff, S .
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Similarly, if Blue cooperates while Red defects, then Blue receives the sucker's payoff S , while Red receives the temptation payoff T .
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The payoff relationship ⁠ $R>P$ ⁠ implies that mutual cooperation is superior to mutual defection, while the payoff relationships ⁠ $T>R$ ⁠ and ⁠ $P>S$ ⁠ imply that defection is the dominant strategy for both agents.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If two players play the prisoner's dilemma more than once in succession, remember their opponent's previous actions, and are allowed to change their strategy accordingly, the game is called the iterated prisoner's dilemma.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In addition to the general form above, the iterative version also requires that ⁠ $2R>T+S$ ⁠, to prevent alternating cooperation and defection giving a greater reward than mutual cooperation.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The iterated prisoner's dilemma is fundamental to some theories of human cooperation and trust.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Assuming that the game effectively models transactions between two people that require trust, cooperative behavior in populations can be modeled by a multi-player iterated version of the game.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In 1975, Grofman and Pool estimated the count of scholarly articles devoted to it at over 2,000.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The iterated prisoner's dilemma is also called the "peace-war game".
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Several variants of the iterated game have been studied, including a version in which players have an exit option after each round.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If the iterated prisoner's dilemma is played a finite number of times and both players know this, then the dominant strategy and Nash equilibrium is to defect in all rounds.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The proof is inductive: one might as well defect on the last turn, since the opponent will not have a chance to later retaliate.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Therefore, both will defect on the last turn.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Thus, the player might as well defect on the second-to-last turn, since the opponent will defect on the last no matter what is done, and so on.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The same applies if the game length is unknown but has a known upper limit.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] For cooperation to emerge between rational players, the number of rounds must be unknown or infinite.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In that case, "always defect" may no longer be a dominant strategy.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] As shown by Robert Aumann in a 1959 paper, rational players repeatedly interacting for indefinitely long games can sustain cooperation.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Specifically, a player may be less willing to cooperate if their counterpart did not cooperate many times, which causes disappointment.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Conversely, as time elapses, the likelihood of cooperation tends to rise, owing to the establishment of a "tacit agreement" among participating players.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In experimental situations, cooperation can occur even when both participants know how many iterations will be played.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] According to a 2019 experimental study in the *American Economic Review* that tested what strategies real-life subjects used in iterated prisoner's dilemma situations with perfect monitoring, the majority of chosen strategies were always to defect, tit-for-tat, and grim trigger.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Which strategy the subjects chose depended on the parameters of the game.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Axelrod invited academic colleagues from around the world to devise computer strategies to compete in an iterated prisoner's dilemma tournament.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The programs that were entered varied widely in algorithmic complexity, initial hostility, capacity for forgiveness, and so forth.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Axelrod discovered that when these encounters were repeated over a long period of time with many players, each with different strategies, greedy strategies tended to do very poorly in the long run while more altruistic strategies did better, as judged purely by self-interest.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] He used this to show a possible mechanism for the evolution of altruistic behavior from mechanisms that are initially purely selfish, by natural selection.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The winning deterministic strategy was tit for tat, developed and entered into the tournament by Anatol Rapoport.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] It was the simplest of any program entered, containing only four lines of BASIC, and won the contest.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The strategy is simply to cooperate on the first iteration of the game; after that, the player does what his or her opponent did on the previous move.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Depending on the situation, a slightly better strategy can be "tit for tat with forgiveness": when the opponent defects, on the next move, the player sometimes cooperates anyway, with a small probability (around 1–5%, depending on the lineup of opponents).
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] This allows for occasional recovery from getting trapped in a cycle of defections.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In contrast to the one-time prisoner's dilemma game, the optimal strategy in the iterated prisoner's dilemma depends upon the strategies of likely opponents, how they will react to defections and cooperation, and the discounting of future payoffs.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] For example, if a population consists entirely of players who always defect, except for one who follows the tit-for-tat strategy, that person is at a slight disadvantage because of the loss on the first turn.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In such a population, the optimal strategy is to defect every time.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] More generally, given a population with a certain percentage of always-defectors with the rest being tit-for-tat players, the optimal strategy depends on the percentage and number of iterations played.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In the strategy called win-stay, lose-switch, faced with a failure to cooperate, the player switches strategy the next turn.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In certain circumstances, Pavlov beats all other strategies by giving preferential treatment to co-players using a similar strategy.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Although tit-for-tat is considered the most robust basic strategy, a team from Southampton University in England introduced a more successful strategy at the 20th-anniversary iterated prisoner's dilemma competition.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] It relied on collusion between programs to achieve the highest number of points for a single program.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The university submitted 60 programs to the competition, which were designed to recognize each other through a series of five to ten moves at the start.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Once this recognition was made, one program would always cooperate and the other would always defect, assuring the maximum number of points for the defector.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If the program realized that it was playing a non-Southampton player, it would continuously defect in an attempt to minimize the competing program's score.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] As a result, the 2004 Prisoners' Dilemma Tournament results show University of Southampton's strategies in the first three places (and a number of positions towards the bottom), despite having fewer wins and many more losses than the GRIM strategy.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The Southampton strategy takes advantage of the fact that multiple entries were allowed in this particular competition and that a team's performance was measured by that of the highest-scoring player (meaning that the use of self-sacrificing players was a form of minmaxing).
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Because of this new rule, this competition also has little theoretical significance when analyzing single-agent strategies as compared to Axelrod's seminal tournament.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] But it provided a basis for analyzing how to achieve cooperative strategies in multi-agent frameworks, especially in the presence of noise.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Long before this new-rules tournament was played, Richard Dawkins, in his book *The Selfish Gene*, pointed out the possibility of such strategies winning if multiple entries were allowed, but wrote that Axelrod would most likely not have allowed them if they had been submitted.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Such strategies also circumvent the rule against communication between players: the Southampton programs' "ten-move dance" allowed them to recognize one another, reinforcing how valuable communication can be in shifting the balance of the game.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Even without implicit collusion between software strategies, tit-for-tat is not always the absolute winner of any given tournament; more precisely, its long-run results over a series of tournaments outperform its rivals, but this does not mean it is the most successful in the short term.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The same applies to tit-for-tat with forgiveness and other optimal strategies.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] This can also be illustrated using the Darwinian ESS simulation.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In such a simulation, tit-for-tat will almost always come to dominate, though nasty strategies will drift in and out of the population because a tit-for-tat population is penetrable by non-retaliating nice strategies, which in turn are easy prey for the nasty strategies.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Dawkins showed that here, no static mix of strategies forms a stable equilibrium, and the system will always oscillate between bounds.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In a stochastic iterated prisoner's dilemma game, strategies are specified in terms of "cooperation probabilities".
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In an encounter between player *X* and player *Y*, *X*'s strategy is specified by a set of probabilities *P* of cooperating with *Y*.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] *P* is a function of the outcomes of their previous encounters or some subset thereof.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If *P* is a function of only their most recent *n* encounters, it is called a "memory-n" strategy.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] A memory-1 strategy is then specified by four cooperation probabilities: $P=\{P_{cc},P_{cd},P_{dc},P_{dd}\}$ , where *Pcd* is the probability that *X* will cooperate in the present encounter given that the previous encounter was characterized by *X* cooperating and *Y* defecting.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If each of the probabilities are either 1 or 0, the strategy is called deterministic.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] An example of a deterministic strategy is the tit-for-tat strategy written as $P=\{1,0,1,0\}$ , in which *X* responds as *Y* did in the previous encounter.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Another is the win-stay, lose switch strategy written as $P=\{1,0,0,1\}$ .
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] It has been shown that for any memory-n strategy there is a corresponding memory-1 strategy that gives the same statistical results, so that only memory-1 strategies need be considered.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] For example, from *X*'s point of view, the probability that the outcome of the present encounter is *cd* given that the previous encounter was *cd* is equal to $M_{cd,cd}=P_{cd}(1-Q_{dc})$ .
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Under these definitions, the iterated prisoner's dilemma qualifies as a stochastic process and *M* is a stochastic matrix, allowing all of the theory of stochastic processes to be applied.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] One result of stochastic theory is that there exists a stationary vector *v* for the matrix *v* such that $v\cdot M=v$ .
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Without loss of generality, it may be specified that *v* is normalized so that the sum of its four components is unity.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The *ij*-th entry in $M^{n}$ will give the probability that the outcome of an encounter between *X* and *Y* will be *j* given that the encounter *n* steps previous is *i*.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In the limit as *n* approaches infinity, *M* will converge to a matrix with fixed values, giving the long-term probabilities of an encounter producing *j* independent of *i*.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In other words, the rows of $M^{\infty }$ will be identical, giving the long-term equilibrium result probabilities of the iterated prisoner's dilemma without the need to explicitly evaluate a large number of interactions.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] It can be seen that *v* is a stationary vector for $M^{n}$ and particularly $M^{\infty }$ , so that each row of $M^{\infty }$ will be equal to *v*.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Thus, the stationary vector specifies the equilibrium outcome probabilities for *X*.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Press and Freeman Dyson published a new class of strategies for the stochastic iterated prisoner's dilemma called "zero-determinant" (ZD) strategies.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The long term payoffs for encounters between *X* and *Y* can be expressed as the determinant of a matrix which is a function of the two strategies and the short term payoff vectors: $s_{x}=D(P,Q,S_{x})$ and $s_{y}=D(P,Q,S_{y})$ , which do not involve the stationary vector *v*.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Any strategies for which $D(P,Q,\alpha S_{x}+\beta S_{y}+\gamma U)=0$ are by definition a ZD strategy, and the long-term payoffs obey the relation $\alpha s_{x}+\beta s_{y}+\gamma =0$ .
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Tit-for-tat is a ZD strategy which is "fair", in the sense of not gaining advantage over the other player.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] But the ZD space also contains strategies that, in the case of two players, can allow one player to unilaterally set the other player's score or alternatively force an evolutionary player to achieve a payoff some percentage lower than his own.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The extorted player could defect, but would thereby hurt himself by getting a lower payoff.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Thus, extortion solutions turn the iterated prisoner's dilemma into a sort of ultimatum game.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Specifically, *X* is able to choose a strategy for which $D(P,Q,\beta S_{y}+\gamma U)=0$ , unilaterally setting *sy* to a specific value within a particular range of values, independent of *Y*'s strategy, offering an opportunity for *X* to "extort" player *Y* (and vice versa).
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] But if *X* tries to set *sx* to a particular value, the range of possibilities is much smaller, consisting only of complete cooperation or complete defection.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] An extension of the iterated prisoner's dilemma is an evolutionary stochastic iterated prisoner's dilemma, in which the relative abundance of particular strategies is allowed to change, with more successful strategies relatively increasing.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] This process may be accomplished by having less successful players imitate the more successful strategies, or by eliminating less successful players from the game, while multiplying the more successful ones.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] It has been shown that unfair ZD strategies are not evolutionarily stable.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Theory and simulations confirm that beyond a critical population size, ZD extortion loses out in evolutionary competition against more cooperative strategies, and as a result, the average payoff in the population increases when the population is larger.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In addition, there are some cases in which extortioners may even catalyze cooperation by helping to break out of a face-off between uniform defectors and win–stay, lose–switch agents.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] While extortionary ZD strategies are not stable in large populations, another ZD class called "generous" strategies is both stable and robust.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] When the population is not too small, these strategies can supplant any other ZD strategy and even perform well against a broad array of generic strategies for iterated prisoner's dilemma, including win–stay, lose–switch.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] This was proven specifically for the donation game by Alexander Stewart and Joshua Plotkin in 2013.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Generous strategies will cooperate with other cooperative players, and in the face of defection, the generous player loses more utility than its rival.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Among good strategies, the generous (ZD) subset performs well when the population is not too small.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If the population is very small, defection strategies tend to dominate.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Most work on the iterated prisoner's dilemma has focused on the discrete case, in which players either cooperate or defect, because this model is relatively simple to analyze.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] However, some researchers have looked at models of the continuous iterated prisoner's dilemma, in which players are able to make a variable contribution to the other player.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Le and Boyd found that in such situations, cooperation is much harder to evolve than in the discrete iterated prisoner's dilemma.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In a continuous prisoner's dilemma, if a population starts off in a non-cooperative equilibrium, players who are only marginally more cooperative than non-cooperators get little benefit from assorting with one another.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] By contrast, in a discrete prisoner's dilemma, tit-for-tat cooperators get a big payoff boost from assorting with one another in a non-cooperative equilibrium, relative to non-cooperators.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Many instances of human interaction and natural processes have payoff matrices like the prisoner's dilemma's.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] It is therefore of interest to the social sciences, such as economics, politics, and sociology, as well as to the biological sciences, such as ethology and evolutionary biology.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Many natural processes have been abstracted into models in which living beings are engaged in endless games of prisoner's dilemma.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In environmental studies, the dilemma is evident in crises such as global climate change.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] It is argued all countries will benefit from a stable climate, but any single country is often hesitant to curb CO2 emissions.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The immediate benefit to any one country from maintaining current behavior is perceived to be greater than the purported eventual benefit to that country if all countries' behavior was changed, therefore explaining the impasse concerning climate-change in 2007.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] An important difference between climate-change politics and the prisoner's dilemma is uncertainty; the extent and pace at which pollution can change climate is not known.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The dilemma faced by governments is therefore different from the prisoner's dilemma in that the payoffs of cooperation are unknown.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] This difference suggests that states will cooperate much less than in a real iterated prisoner's dilemma, so that the probability of avoiding a possible climate catastrophe is much smaller than that suggested by a game-theoretical analysis of the situation using a real iterated prisoner's dilemma.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Thomas Osang and Arundhati Nandy provide a theoretical explanation with proofs for a regulation-driven win-win situation along the lines of Michael Porter's hypothesis, in which government regulation of competing firms is substantial.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Cooperative behavior of many animals can be understood as an example of the iterated prisoner's dilemma.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Often animals engage in long-term partnerships; for example, guppies inspect predators cooperatively in groups, and they are thought to punish non-cooperative inspectors.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Vampire bats are social animals that engage in reciprocal food exchange.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Applying the payoffs from the prisoner's dilemma can help explain this behavior.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In addiction research and behavioral economics, George Ainslie points out that addiction can be cast as an intertemporal prisoner's dilemma problem between the present and future selves of the addict.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In this case, "defecting" means relapsing, where not relapsing both today and in the future is by far the best outcome.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The case where one abstains today but relapses in the future is the worst outcome: in some sense, the discipline and self-sacrifice involved in abstaining today have been "wasted" because the future relapse means that the addict is right back where they started and will have to start over.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Relapsing today and tomorrow is a slightly "better" outcome, because while the addict is still addicted, they haven't put the effort in to trying to stop.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In *The Science of Trust*, John Gottman defines good relationships as those where partners know not to enter into mutual defection behavior, or at least not to get dynamically stuck there in a loop.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In cognitive neuroscience, fast brain signaling associated with processing different rounds may indicate choices at the next round.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Mutual cooperation outcomes entail brain activity changes predictive of how quickly a person will cooperate in kind at the next opportunity; this activity may be linked to basic homeostatic and motivational processes, possibly increasing the likelihood of short-cutting into mutual cooperation.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The prisoner's dilemma has been called the *E. coli* of social psychology, and it has been used widely to research various topics such as oligopolistic competition and collective action to produce a collective good.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Advertising is sometimes cited as a real example of the prisoner's dilemma.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] When cigarette advertising was legal in the United States, competing cigarette manufacturers had to decide how much money to spend on advertising.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The effectiveness of Firm A's advertising was partially determined by the advertising conducted by Firm B.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Likewise, the profit derived from advertising for Firm B is affected by the advertising conducted by Firm A.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If both Firm A and Firm B chose to advertise during a given period, then the advertisement from each firm negates the other's, receipts remain constant, and expenses increase due to the cost of advertising.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Both firms would benefit from a reduction in advertising.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] However, should Firm B choose not to advertise, Firm A could benefit greatly by advertising.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Nevertheless, the optimal amount of advertising by one firm depends on how much advertising the other undertakes.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] As the best strategy is dependent on what the other firm chooses there is no dominant strategy, which makes it slightly different from a prisoner's dilemma.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The outcome is similar, though, in that both firms would be better off were they to advertise less than in the equilibrium.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Sometimes cooperative behaviors do emerge in business situations.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] For instance, cigarette manufacturers endorsed the making of laws banning cigarette advertising, understanding that this would reduce costs and increase profits across the industry.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Without enforceable agreements, members of a cartel are also involved in a (multi-player) prisoner's dilemma.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] "Cooperating" typically means agreeing to a price floor, while "defecting" means selling under this minimum level, instantly taking business from other cartel members.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Anti-trust authorities want potential cartel members to mutually defect, ensuring the lowest possible prices for consumers.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Doping in sport has been cited as an example of a prisoner's dilemma.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Two competing athletes have the option to use an illegal and/or dangerous drug to boost their performance.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If neither athlete takes the drug, then neither gains an advantage.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If only one does, then that athlete gains a significant advantage over the competitor, reduced by the legal and/or medical dangers of having taken the drug.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] But if both athletes take the drug, the benefits cancel out and only the dangers remain, putting them both in a worse position than if neither had doped.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In international relations theory, the prisoner's dilemma is often used to demonstrate why cooperation fails in situations when cooperation between states is collectively optimal but individually suboptimal.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] A classic example is the security dilemma, whereby an increase in one state's security (such as increasing its military strength) leads other states to fear for their own security out of fear of offensive action.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Consequently, security-increasing measures can lead to tensions, escalation or conflict with one or more other parties, producing an outcome which no party truly desires.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The security dilemma is particularly intense in situations when it is hard to distinguish offensive weapons from defensive weapons, and offense has the advantage in any conflict over defense.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Critics of realism argue that iteration and extending the shadow of the future are solutions to the prisoner's dilemma.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] When actors play the prisoner's dilemma once, they have incentives to defect, but when they expect to play it repeatedly, they have greater incentives to cooperate.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Many real-life dilemmas involve multiple players.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Although metaphorical, Garrett Hardin's tragedy of the commons may be viewed as an example of a multi-player generalization of the prisoner's dilemma: each villager makes a choice for personal gain or restraint.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The collective reward for unanimous or frequent defection is very low payoffs and the destruction of the commons.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The commons are not always exploited: William Poundstone, in a book about the prisoner's dilemma, describes a situation in New Zealand where newspaper boxes are left unlocked.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] It is possible for people to take a paper without paying (defecting), but very few do, feeling that if they do not pay then neither will others, destroying the system.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Subsequent research by Elinor Ostrom, winner of the 2009 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences, hypothesized that the tragedy of the commons is oversimplified, with the negative outcome influenced by outside influences.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Without complicating pressures, groups communicate and manage the commons among themselves for their mutual benefit, enforcing social norms to preserve the resource and achieve the maximum good for the group, an example of effecting the best-case outcome for prisoner's dilemma.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The prisoner's dilemma has been used in various academic settings to illustrate the complexities of cooperation and competition.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] One notable example is the classroom experiment conducted by sociology professor Dan Chambliss at Hamilton College in the 1980s.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Starting in 1981, Chambliss proposed that if no student took the final exam, everyone would receive an A, but if even one student took it, those who didn't would receive a zero.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In 1988, John Werner, a first-year student, successfully organized his classmates to boycott the exam, demonstrating a practical application of game theory and the prisoner's dilemma concept.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Nearly 25 years later, a similar incident occurred at Johns Hopkins University in 2013.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Professor Peter Fröhlich's grading policy scaled final exams according to the highest score, meaning that if everyone received the same score, they would all get an A.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Students in Fröhlich's classes organized a boycott of the final exam, ensuring that no one took it.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] As a result, every student received an A.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] These examples highlight how the prisoner's dilemma can be used to explore cooperative behavior and strategic decision-making in educational contexts.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Douglas Hofstadter suggested that people often find problems such as the prisoner's dilemma problem easier to understand when it is illustrated in the form of a simple game, or trade-off.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] This payoff matrix has also been used on the British television programs *Trust Me*, *Shafted*, *The Bank Job*, *Golden Balls*, and *The Inner Circle*, and on the U.S. game show *Take It All*, as well as for the winning couple on the reality shows *Bachelor Pad* and *Love Island*.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] A team of economists analyzed data from *Golden Balls* and found that cooperation was "surprisingly high" for amounts of money that would be consequential in the real world but were comparatively low in the context of the game.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The dilemma is also a Game Mechanic on *The Traitors* if multiple Traitors remain in the game as finalists.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] This happened on the second season finale on *The Traitors Australia*; a three-player variation of the dilemma arose for the three Traitor Finalists.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] They were given a choice to "share" or "steal" the prize pot.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If all three chose to share, each would receive a third of the pot.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If one or two traitors chose to steal, those who shared would win nothing and the pot would be divided among those who stole.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If all three chose to steal, no one would win anything.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Researchers from the University of Lausanne and the University of Edinburgh have suggested that the "Iterated Snowdrift Game" may more closely reflect real-world social situations, although this model is actually a chicken game.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In this model, the risk of being exploited through defection is lower, and individuals always gain from taking the cooperative choice.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The snowdrift game imagines two drivers who are stuck on opposite sides of a snowdrift, each of whom is given the option of shoveling snow to clear a path or remaining in their car.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] A player's highest payoff comes from leaving the opponent to clear all the snow by themselves, but the opponent is still nominally rewarded for their work.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] This may better reflect real-world scenarios, the researchers giving the example of two scientists collaborating on a report, both of whom would benefit if the other worked harder.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] "But when your collaborator doesn't do any work, it's probably better for you to do all the work yourself.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In coordination games, players must coordinate their strategies for a good outcome.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] An example is two cars that abruptly meet in a blizzard; each must choose whether to swerve left or right.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] If both swerve left, or both right, the cars do not collide.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The local left- and right-hand traffic convention helps to co-ordinate their actions.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Symmetrical co-ordination games include Stag hunt and Bach or Stravinsky.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] A more general set of games is asymmetric.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] As in the prisoner's dilemma, the best outcome is cooperation, and there are motives for defection.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Unlike the symmetric prisoner's dilemma, though, one player has more to lose and/or more to gain than the other.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Some such games have been described as a prisoner's dilemma in which one prisoner has an alibi, hence the term "alibi game".
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Such behavior may depend on the experiment's social norms around fairness.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Hannu Rajaniemi set the opening scene of his *The Quantum Thief* trilogy in a "dilemma prison".
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The main theme of the series has been described as the "inadequacy of a binary universe" and the ultimate antagonist is a character called the All-Defector.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The first book in the series was published in 2010, with the two sequels, *The Fractal Prince* and *The Causal Angel*, published in 2012 and 2014, respectively.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] A game modeled after the iterated prisoner's dilemma is a central focus of the 2012 video game *Zero Escape: Virtue's Last Reward* and a minor part in its 2016 sequel *Zero Escape: Zero Time Dilemma*.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In *The Mysterious Benedict Society and the Prisoner's Dilemma* by Trenton Lee Stewart, the main characters start by playing a version of the game and escaping from the "prison" altogether.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Later, they become actual prisoners and escape once again.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] In *The Adventure Zone: Balance* during *The Suffering Game* subarc, the player characters are twice presented with the prisoner's dilemma during their time in two liches' domain, once cooperating and once defecting.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Corey's novel *Tiamat's Wrath*, Colonel Jason Ilich explains the prisoner's dilemma to Winston Duarte's daughter, Teresa, to train her in strategic thinking.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The prisoner's dilemma is commonly used as a thinking tool in moral philosophy as an illustration of the potential tension between the benefit of the individual and the benefit of the community.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Both the one-shot and the iterated prisoner's dilemma have applications in moral philosophy.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Indeed, many of the moral situations, such as genocide, are not easily repeated more than once.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Moreover, in many situations, the previous rounds' outcomes are unknown to the players, since they are not necessarily the same (e.g. interaction with a panhandler on the street).
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] The philosopher David Gauthier uses the prisoner's dilemma to show how morality and rationality can conflict.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Some game theorists have criticized the use of the prisoner's dilemma as a thinking tool in moral philosophy.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Kenneth Binmore argued that the prisoner's dilemma does not accurately describe the game played by humanity, which he argues is closer to a coordination game.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Other game theorists see the prisoner's dilemma as arising out of uncertainty over possible non-dilemma games perceived by the players.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] Steven Kuhn suggests that these views may be reconciled by considering that moral behavior can modify the payoff matrix of a game, transforming it from a prisoner's dilemma into other games.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] A prisoner's dilemma is considered "impure" if a mixed strategy may give better expected payoffs than a pure strategy.
[src:game-theory/prisoner-s-dilemma] This creates the interesting possibility that the moral action from a utilitarian perspective (i.e., aiming at maximizing the good of an action) may require randomization of one's strategy, such as cooperating with 80% chance and defecting with 20% chance.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] In cooperative game theory, the **Shapley value** is a method (solution concept) for fairly distributing the total gains or costs among a group of players who have collaborated.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] For example, in a team project where each member contributed differently, the Shapley value provides a way to determine how much credit or blame each member deserves.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] It was named in honor of Lloyd Shapley, who introduced it in 1951.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] The Shapley value determines each player's contribution by considering how much the overall outcome changes when they join each possible combination of other players, and then averaging those changes.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] In essence, it calculates each player's average marginal contribution across all possible coalitions.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] It is the only solution that satisfies four fundamental properties: efficiency, symmetry, additivity, and the dummy player (or null player) property, which are widely accepted as defining a fair distribution.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] This method is used in many fields, from dividing profits in business partnerships to understanding feature importance in machine learning.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] Suppose we have a situation where players can win certain rewards by cooperating (forming a coalition) to accomplish a task; such situations are often called coalitional games.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] For a coalition (set of players) S , we define the *payoff* or *value* function $v(S)$ as the total sum of payoffs that the members of S can obtain by cooperating.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] The Shapley value is one way to divide up the value created by a coalition between its members.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] It is a "fair" distribution in the sense that it is the only distribution with certain desirable properties (listed below).
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] where n is the total number of players and the sum extends over all subsets S of N not containing player i , including the empty set.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] Also note that ${n \choose k}$ is the binomial coefficient.
