[src:game-theory/shapley-value] In other words, the 'total value' of the coalition S comes from summing up the *synergies* of each possible subset of S .
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] using the Inclusion exclusion principle.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] where the sum is over all subsets S of N that include player i .
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] In other words, the synergy of each coalition is divided equally between all members.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] This can be interpreted visually with a Venn diagram.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] In the first example diagram above, each region has been labeled with the synergy bonus of the corresponding coalition.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] The total value produced by a coalition is the sum of synergy bonuses of the composing subcoalitions - in the example, the coalition of the players labeled "You" and "Emma" would produce a profit of $30+20+40=90$ dollars, as compared to their individual profits of $30$ and $20$ dollars respectively.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] The synergies are then split equally among each member of the subcoalition that contributes that synergy - as displayed in the second diagram.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] Consider a simplified description of a business.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] An owner, *o*, provides crucial capital in the sense that, without him/her, no gains can be obtained.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] There are *m* workers *w*1,...,*w**m*, each of whom contributes an amount *p* to the total profit.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] Computing the Shapley value for this coalition game leads to a value of ⁠*mp*/2⁠ for the owner and ⁠*p*/2⁠ for each one of the *m* workers.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] This can be understood from the perspective of synergy.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] so the only coalitions that generate synergy are one-to-one between the owner and any individual worker.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] The result can also be understood from the perspective of averaging over all orders.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] A given worker joins the coalition after the owner (and therefore contributes *p*) in half of the orders and thus makes an average contribution of ${\frac {p}{2}}$ upon joining.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] When the owner joins, on average half the workers have already joined, so the owner's average contribution upon joining is ${\frac {mp}{2}}$ .
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] The glove game is a coalitional game where the players have left- and right-hand gloves and the goal is to form pairs.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] where players 1 and 2 have right-hand gloves and player 3 has a left-hand glove.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] where R is an ordering of the players and $P_{i}^{R}$ is the set of players in N which precede i in the order R.
