[src:game-theory/shapley-value] The Shapley value has many desirable properties, including satisfying the four properties of efficiency, symmetry, linearity and null player (or dummy player).
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] since $\sum _{i\in N}v(P_{i}^{R}\cup \left\{i\right\})-v(P_{i}^{R})$ is a telescoping sum and there are $|N|!$ different orderings R .
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] for every subset S of N which contains neither i nor j , then $\varphi _{i}(v)=\varphi _{j}(v)$ .
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] This property is also called *equal treatment of equals*.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] The Shapley value $\varphi _{i}(v)$ of a null player i in a game v is zero.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] A player i is *null* in v if $v(S\cup \{i\})=v(S)$ for all coalitions S that do not contain i .
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] If v is a subadditive set function, i.e., if $v(S\cup T)\leq v(S)+v(T)$ , then for each agent i : $\varphi _{i}(v)\leq v(\{i\})$ .
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] Similarly, if v is a superadditive set function, i.e., if $v(S\cup T)\geq v(S)+v(T)$ for $S\cap T=\emptyset$ , then for each agent i : $\varphi _{i}(v)\geq v(\{i\})$ .
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] So, if the cooperation has positive synergy, all agents (weakly) gain, and if it has negative synergy, all agents (weakly) lose.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] If i and j are two agents, and w is a gain function that is identical to v except that the roles of i and j have been exchanged, then $\varphi _{i}(v)=\varphi _{j}(w)$ .
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] This means that the labeling of the agents doesn't play a role in the assignment of their gains.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] The Shapley value can be defined as a function which uses only the marginal contributions of player i as the arguments.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] In their 1974 book, Lloyd Shapley and Robert Aumann extended the concept of the Shapley value to infinite games (defined with respect to a non-atomic measure), creating the diagonal formula.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] This was later extended by Jean-François Mertens and Abraham Neyman.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] As seen above, the value of an n-person game associates with each player the expectation of their contribution to the worth of the coalition of players before them in a random ordering of all the players.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] When there are many players and each individual plays only a minor role, the set of all players preceding a given one is heuristically thought of as a good sample of all players.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] The value of a given infinitesimal player ds is then defined as "their" contribution to the worth of a "perfect" sample of all the players.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] Here tI is a perfect sample of the all-player set I containing a proportion t of all the players, and $tI+ds$ is the coalition obtained after ds joins tI.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] This is the heuristic form of the diagonal formula.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] Above μ can be vector valued (as long as the function is defined and differentiable on the range of μ, the above formula makes sense).
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] In the argument above if the measure contains atoms $\mu (tI)=t\mu (I)$ is no longer true—this is why the diagonal formula mostly applies to non-atomic games.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] Two approaches were deployed to extend this diagonal formula when the function f is no longer differentiable.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] Mertens goes back to the original formula and takes the derivative after the integral thereby benefiting from the smoothing effect.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] This works for example for majority games—while the original diagonal formula cannot be used directly.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] How Mertens further extends this by identifying symmetries that the Shapley value should be invariant upon, and averaging over such symmetries to create further smoothing effect commuting averages with the derivative operation as above.
[src:game-theory/shapley-value] The Shapley value only assigns values to the individual agents.
